{"title_page": "Clonmel", "text_new": "{{other uses}}\n{{EngvarB|date=November 2015}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=November 2015}}\n\n{{Infobox settlement\n|settlement_type        = Town\n|name                   = Clonmel\n|native_name             = {{Pad top italic|Cluain Meala}}\n|image_shield           = Clonmel COA.png\n|shield_size            = 150px\n|motto = ''Fidelis in \u00c6ternum''{{spaces|2}}<small>([[Latin language|Latin]])</small><br />\"Faithful Forever\"\n|pushpin_map            = Ireland\n|pushpin_label_position = right\n|pushpin_map_caption    = Location in Ireland\n|coordinates            = {{coord|52.3539|-7.7116|dim:100000_region:IE|display=inline,title}}\n|blank_name_sec1        = Irish Grid Reference\n|blank_info_sec1        = {{iem4ibx|S199229}}\n|area_total_km2         = 10.5\n|unit_pref              = Metric\n|elevation_m            = 20\n|subdivision_type       = Country\n|subdivision_name       = Ireland\n|subdivision_type1      = [[Provinces of Ireland|Province]]\n|subdivision_name1      = [[Munster]]\n|subdivision_type2      = [[Counties of Ireland|County]]\n|subdivision_name2      = [[County Tipperary]]\n|population_as_of       = 2016\n|population_footnotes   = <ref name=\"sapmap2016\">{{cite web|url =\nhttp://census.cso.ie/sapmap2016/Results.aspx?Geog_Type=ST2016&Geog_Code=64AB345C-A63F-46C4-A2D5-8F5447FCD731#SAPMAP_T1_100 | publisher = [[Central Statistics Office (Ireland)|CSO]] | work = Census 2016 | title = Sapmap Area - Settlements - Clonmel | date = 2016 | accessdate = 12 January 2018 }}</ref>\n|population_total       = 17,140   \n|population_density_km2 = 1,636.4\n|website                =\n|subdivision_type3      = D\u00e1il \u00c9ireann\n|subdivision_name3      = [[Tipperary (D\u00e1il constituency)|Tipperary]]\n|subdivision_type4      = EU Parliament\n|subdivision_name4      = [[South (European Parliament constituency)|South]]\n| area_code_type = [[Telephone numbers in the Republic of Ireland|Telephone area code]]\n| area_code = 052\n| postal_code_type        =[[Eircode]]\n| postal_code             =E91\n|timezone                = [[Western European Time|WET]]\n|utc_offset              = 0\n|timezone_DST            = [[Irish Standard Time|IST]]\n|utc_offset_DST          = +1\n|image_skyline          = Clonmel.jpg\n|image_caption          = The Quays, Clonmel.\n}}\n'''Clonmel''' ({{Irish place name|Cluain Meala|honey meadow}}) is the [[county town]] and largest settlement of [[County Tipperary]], [[Republic of Ireland|Ireland]]. The town is noted in Irish history for its resistance to the [[Cromwellian conquest of Ireland|Cromwellian army]] which sacked the towns of [[Drogheda]] and [[Wexford]]. With the exception of the [[townland]] of Suir Island, most of the borough is situated in the [[Civil parishes in Ireland|civil parish]] of \"St Mary's\"<ref>[https://www.logainm.ie/2335.aspx Placenames Database of Ireland] - St Mary's, Clonmel civil parish</ref> which is part of the ancient [[Barony (Ireland)|barony]] of [[Iffa and Offa East]].\n\n==Population==\nThe 2016 Census used a new boundary created by the [[Central Statistics Office (Ireland)|Central Statistics Office]] (CSO) to define the town of Clonmel and Environs resulting in a population figure of 17,140. This new boundary omitted part of the Clonmel Borough Boundary which the CSO had defined as Legal Town for the 2011 census 11.55&nbsp;km/sq. All of the 2011 census CSO environ in Co Waterford have been omitted as well as parts of CSO Environ of Clonmel in Co Tipperary. The CSO as part of the 11 May 2017 release of data compared their new 2016 CSO boundary with its population of 17,140 with the 2011 CSO Clonmel Environ boundary which is a larger area and had a resulting greater population of 17,908. The CSO are not comparing the same area and are incorrectly recorded a population decline of 768 (-4.3%).\n\nClonmel Borough (CSO Legal Town 2011, 11.55&nbsp;km/sq) had a population of 15,793 in 2011, another 2115 people were in the rural environs of Clonmel comprising Marlfield, Ardgeeha Upper (Cashel Rd), Boherduff (Fethard Rd) in County Tipperary and in [[County Waterford]] the area between the Dungarvan Rd and Mountain Rd.<ref>[http://beyond2020.cso.ie/Census/TableViewer/tableView.aspx?ReportId=109359 C.S.O. Census 2011] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130622071349/http://beyond2020.cso.ie/Census/TableViewer/tableView.aspx?ReportId=109359 |date=22 June 2013 }}</ref>\n\n==Etymology==\nThe name Clonmel is derived from the [[anglicisation]] of the Irish name ''Cluain Meala'' meaning honey meadow or honey vale. It is not clearly known when it got this name; many suppose that it came from the fertility of the soil and the richness of the country in which it is situated.<ref>[https://archive.org/details/historyclonmel00burkgoog History of Clonmel (1907)]</ref>\n\n== History ==\n[[File:Old Saint Marys, Clonmel.jpg|thumb|250px|right|Old St. Mary's Church]]\n\n===Town walls===\nClonmel grew significantly in [[medieval]] times, and many remainders of this period can be found in the town. A small section of the town walls remain in place near [[Old St. Mary's Church (Clonmel)|Old St. Mary's Church]] . This building is one of the main architectural features of the town. It was originally built in the 14th century or earlier but has been reconstructed or renovated on numerous occasions. The church was fortified early in its history, the town being strategically important, initially for the [[Earl of Ormonde (Irish)|Earls of Ormonde]], and later the [[Earl of Kildare]]. Some fortified parts of the church were destroyed or damaged during the [[Cromwellian conquest of Ireland|Cromwellian occupation]]. One of the former entry points into the town is now the site of the 'West Gate', a 19th-century reconstruction of an older structure. There were originally three gates in the walled town, North, East and West \u2013 with the South being protected by the river [[Suir]] and the [[Comeragh Mountains]]. The 'West Gate' is now an open arched entrance on to O'Connell street, the main street of the town.\n\n===Corporation regalia===\nUnder a charter granted by [[James I of England]], Clonmel became a [[Borough|Free Borough]] on 5 July 1608, and the Mayor and officers of the town were granted power to \"name, elect and constitute one Swordbearer and three Sergeants-at-Mace\". The present sword and two silver maces date only from Cromwellian times. The sword, of [[Toledo, Spain|Toledo]] manufacture, was donated by Sir Thomas Stanley in 1656 and displays the Arms and motto of the town. The larger mace is stamped 1663.<ref>{{cite book|last=Burke  |first= William P. |title=History of Clonmel|publisher=N. Harvey & co. for the Clonmel Library Committee|year=1907|pages=[https://archive.org/details/historyclonmel00burkgoog/page/n265 235]\u2013237|url=https://archive.org/details/historyclonmel00burkgoog}}</ref>\n\n===Cromwellian period===\n[[File:Western Tower, Clonmel's Town Wall..jpg|thumb|120px|right|One of the remaining towers of Clonmel's defensive wall]]\n[[File:371 of 'Cromwell in Ireland, a history of Cromwell's Irish Campaign ... with map, plans and illustrations' (11164473114).jpg|thumb|400px|Map of 17th-century Clonmel. Note \"Irishtown\" in the west.]]\n[[Oliver Cromwell]] [[Siege of Clonmel|laid siege to Clonmel]] in May 1650. The walls were eventually breached, but [[Hugh Dubh O'Neill]], the commander of the town's garrison, inflicted heavy losses on the [[New Model Army]] when they tried to storm the breach. That night, O'Neill, deciding that further resistance was hopeless due to a lack of ammunition, led his soldiers and camp followers out of the town under cover of darkness. The story is told that Cromwell became suspicious of O'Neill's desperate situation when a silver bullet was discharged by the townspeople at his troops outside the walls.<ref>{{cite book|last=Curry|first=William|title=The Dublin University Magazine |publisher=William Curry, Jun., and Co.|year=1853|volume=v. 42|url=https://books.google.com/?id=5NoRAAAAYAAJ&pg=PA329&dq=clonmel+%22silver+bullet%22|accessdate=27 June 2009}}</ref> The following morning, 18 May 1650, mayor John White was able to surrender the town on good terms as Cromwell was still unaware of the garrison's escape just hours before. Although feeling deceived, he did not put the inhabitants 'to the sword' as occurred elsewhere.\n\n[[File:Trial of Irish patriots Clonmel.jpg|thumb|left|200px|[[Young Irelanders]] stand trial before [[Francis Blackburne|Justice Blackburne]] at Clonmel, 1848]]\n\n===19th century===\nA permanent military presence was established in the town with the completion of [[Kickham Barracks]] in 1805.<ref>{{cite web|url= http://uccplanningsoc.files.wordpress.com/2012/11/kickham-barracks-development-proposal.pdf|title=The Kickham Army Barracks Development Proposal|publisher=University College Cork|accessdate=11 November 2014}}</ref>\n\nFollowing the failed attempt at rebellion near [[Ballingarry, South Tipperary|Ballingarry]] in 1848, the captured leaders of the [[Young Irelanders]] were brought to Clonmel for trial.<ref>{{cite book|last=McConville|first=Se\u00e1n|title=Irish political prisoners, 1848\u20131922: theatres of war|publisher=Routledge|year=2003|page=42|isbn=978-0-415-21991-4|url=https://books.google.com/?id=rLrsi3hpXIQC&pg=PA42|accessdate=7 July 2009}}</ref> The event was followed with great interest internationally and for its duration brought journalists from around the country and Britain to [[Clonmel Courthouse]]. Standing in the dock in the image opposite are [[Thomas Francis Meagher]], [[Terence MacManus]] and [[Patrick O'Donoghue (Young Irelander)|Patrick O'Donoghue]]. Their co-defendant, [[William Smith O'Brien]] was also sentenced to be [[hanged, drawn and quartered]], the last occasions such a sentence was handed down in Ireland. When delivering the guilty verdict, the foreman of the [[Grand jury#Ireland|Grand Jury]], R.M. Southcote Mansergh, great grandfather of the academic [[Nicholas Mansergh]] stated:\n<blockquote>\nWe earnestly recommend the prisoner to the merciful consideration of the Government, being unanimously of opinion that for many reasons his life should be spared.<ref>{{cite book|last=Mansergh|first=Nicholas|title=Nationalism and independence: selected Irish papers Irish History Series |editor=Diana Mansergh|publisher=Cork University Press|year=1997|isbn=978-1-85918-106-5|url=https://books.google.com/?id=f7OC7YQkFwYC&pg=PA124&dq=%22southcote+mansergh%22&q=%22southcote%20mansergh%22|accessdate=15 August 2009}}</ref>\n</blockquote>\nThe sentences of O'Brien and other members of the [[Irish Confederation]] were eventually commuted to [[Penal transportation|transportation]] for life to [[Van Diemen's Land]]. A conspiracy to rescue the prisoners on 8 November led by [[John O'Leary (Fenian)|John O'Leary]] and [[Philip Gray]] was betrayed, and resulted in the arrest at 'The Wilderness' of seventeen armed rebels led by Gray.<ref>O'Donnell, Sean : [https://books.google.com/books?id=ibJnAAAAMAAJ&q=clonmel+anatomy+of+an+irish+town&dq=clonmel+anatomy+of+an+irish+town&pgis=1 ''Clonmel \u2013 1840\u20131900 Anatomy of an Irish Town''] 1999 {{ISBN|978-0-906602-51-5}} p153</ref>\n\n===20th century===\nClonmel was the location of the foundation of the [[Labour Party (Ireland)|Labour Party]] in 1912 by [[James Connolly]], [[James Larkin]] and [[William O'Brien]] as the political wing of the [[Irish Trades Union Congress]].<ref>[http://www.labour.ie/party/history.html labour.ie]</ref>\n\n===21st century===\nIn November 2015 the town was the location of Ireland's first marriage between two men.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Dalby|first1=James|title=First Same-Sex Marriage Ceremoney Held in Ireland|publisher=New York Times|date=19 November 2015}}</ref>\n\n== Politics and government ==\nClonmel had a Borough Council until 2014. It was one of five Borough Councils in Ireland. It had 12 elected representatives (councillors). John Hackett was the first Mayor and Pat English was the last Mayor of Clonmel Borough Council.\n\nFor local elections in 2014 the District of Cahir-Clonmel elected nine members to [[Tipperary County Council]].\n\n===National===\nClonmel belongs to the [[Tipperary (D\u00e1il constituency)|Tipperary constituency]] which elects five [[Teachta D\u00e1la|TD]]s to [[D\u00e1il \u00c9ireann]] (the Irish Parliament).\n\nIn the 2016 General Election [[Mattie McGrath]] (Independent), [[Michael Lowry]] (Independent), [[Alan Kelly (politician)|Alan Kelly]] ([[Labour Party (Ireland)|Labour Party]]), [[Jackie Cahill]] ([[Fianna F\u00e1il]]) and [[S\u00e9amus Healy]] ([[Workers and Unemployed Action]]) won the five seats.\n\nThe [[2020 Irish General Election]] was supposed to  be postponed due to the sudden death of Independent candidate Marese Skehan [https://www.bbc.com/news/world-europe-51369150]. This was because it was a requirement under the 1992 Electoral Act Section 62. However, Attorney General S\u00e9amus Woulfe advised the Government that the entire general election could be open to a legal challenge if the Tipperary poll did not go ahead. So the election continued on Saturday February 8 along with the rest of the country. It was [[Michael Lowry]] (Independent) elected on the first count winning 18.1% of the first preference votes. [[Mattie McGrath]] (Independent) and [[Martin Browne (politician)|Martin Browne]] ([[Sinn F\u00e9in]]) were elected on the 8th count. While [[Alan Kelly (politician)|Alan Kelly]] ([[Labour Party (Ireland)|Labour Party]]) and [[Jackie Cahill]] ([[Fianna F\u00e1il]]) made it in on the 9th count.[https://www.rte.ie/news/election-2020/results/#/national/tipperary] This still gives Clonmel no sitting TD as town mayor Garret Ahern was not elected. \n{{Clear}}\n\n[[File:A street in Clonmel.jpg|thumb|A street in Clonmel, Ireland]]\n\n==Geography==\nThe town is built in the valley of the [[River Suir]]. It divides the town which is mainly located on the north bank. To the south the town is surround by the [[Comeragh Mountains]] and [[Slievenamon]] to the northeast. To the north, east and west is some of Irelands richest farmland known as the [[Golden Vale]]. The town covers a land area of approximately 11.59km2.\n\n===Climate===\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"width: 50%; margin: 0 auto 0 auto;\"\n|+ '''Climate Table'''\n!\n! Jan\n! Feb\n! Mar\n! Apr\n! May\n! Jun\n! Jul\n! Aug\n! Sep\n! Oct\n! Nov\n! Dec\n!Year\n|-\n! Average daily maximum temperature (\u00b0C)\n| 8\n| 8\n| 10\n| 13\n| 16\n| 18\n| 20\n| 20\n| 18\n| 14\n| 10\n| 8\n| '''14'''\n|-\n! Average daily minimum temperature (\u00b0C)\n| 3\n| 3\n| 4\n| 5\n| 7\n| 10\n| 12\n| 12\n| 10\n| 7\n| 5\n| 4\n| '''7'''\n|-\n! Mean total rainfall (cm)\n| 5.34\n| 4.29\n| 3.84\n| 3.98\n| 3.40\n| 3.72\n| 3.38\n| 4.22\n| 4.33\n| 6.35\n| 5.07\n| 5.03\n| '''52.95'''\n|-\n| colspan=\"15\" style=\"text-align: center;\" | <small>'''Source:''' MSN Weather</small>\n|}\n\n===Flood defences===\nThe [[River Suir]] floods the local area after very heavy rainfalls in the up-river catchment area of 2,173&nbsp;km<sup>2</sup>. The [[Office of Public Works]] (OPW) completed and installed a Flood Forecasting System which has been used since 2007. The flood of 2015 had a flow of 390m<sup>3</sup>/s, 2004 had a flow of 354m<sup>3</sup>/s with the flood of 2000 having a flow of 353m<sup>3</sup>/s. The 2015 flood was the worst since that of 1946, which had seen a flow of 479m<sup>3</sup>/s. Phase 1 of the Clonmel Flood Defence (planned to cope with a [[100-year flood]]) started in 2007. It was scheduled to be completed by late 2009. Phases two and three were completion by 2012. Property omitted from Phase 1 along the convent road were protected in 2014 and the access to the river for the workmans boat club was also raised. \nFlooding of October 2014 was less than a 1\u20135 flood with a flow of 300m<sup>3</sup>/s. As part of a media exercise by the OPW the barrier were all put up.<ref>{{cite web|last1=OPW|title=Office of Public Works \u2013 Flood Defence Management|url=http://www.opw.ie/floodriskmanagement/floodriskmanagementoperations/majorflooddefenceschemes/clonmelflooddefencescheme/#.VFZYAsV_shY|accessdate=2 November 2014|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20141102175128/http://www.opw.ie/floodriskmanagement/floodriskmanagementoperations/majorflooddefenceschemes/clonmelflooddefencescheme/#.VFZYAsV_shY|archivedate=2 November 2014|df=dmy-all}}</ref> The flood defence consists of demountable barriers, walls and earth banks. Flooding occurred at the Gashouse Bridge, Coleville Road, Davis Road, the Quays and the Old Bridge area before the flood defences. Clonmel is not tidal as the tide turns above the [[Glanbia|Miloko]] chocolate crumb factory in [[Carrick-on-Suir]]. Flood waters spill onto the land above Miloko on the [[County Waterford]] side of the river.\n\n==Economy==\n\n===Retail===\nClonmel's main shopping streets are Gladstone Street and O'Connell Street which are home to many national and international retailers such as [[Elverys Sports]], [[Penneys]], [[River Island]], [[Easons]] and [[Lifestyle Sports]] to name a few. More local retailers can be found along the streets branching off from those streets.\n\nThe Showgrounds Shopping Centre built during the [[Celtic Tiger]] can be found only 1&nbsp;km from the town centre. This modern shopping centre built on the towns original show ground, houses retailers such as [[M&S]], [[TKMaxx]], [[Argos (retailer)|Argos]] and [[Golden Discs]].\n\nThe Poppyfield Retail Park is located on the outskirts of the town. It has many stores such as DID Electrical, [[Supervalue]], Maxi Zoo, [[Woodie's DIY|Woodie's]] and World of Wonder. The retail park has food vendors being [[KFC]], [[Costa Coffee]], the Red Herring and Esquires Coffee. There is also a hotel on the site.\n\n===Industry===\n[[File:Bulmers factory clonmel.png|thumb|right|200px|Bulmers cider factory]]\nIn recent times, Clonmel have become home to many large multi-national companies, particularly in the medical area. The two biggest medical companies in the town are [[Abbott Laboratories|Abbott]] and [[Boston Scientific]], both of which manufacture implantable devices. Two other multi-national pharmaceutical companies are [[Merck & Co.]] and Pinewood Healthcare found less than twenty minutes away.\n\nThe town produces many beverages both alcoholic and non-alcoholic. [[Bulmers (Republic of Ireland)|Bulmers]] [[cider]], also known as [[Bulmers (Ireland)|Magners]] outside Ireland, was founded in the town and is still brewed in a new complex {{convert|2|km}} east of the town with orchards surrounding it. The original brewery in the town is set to turn in to a new visitor attraction. Glenpatrick Spring Water bottles still, carbonated and flavoured water from the limestone rocks beneath [[Slievenamon]] for many big supermarket chains in Ireland and the UK such as Tesco and M&S.\n\nClonmel is home to international engineering and construction groups such as [[Kentz]] and Sepam who were both founded in the town. Sepam has helped in the construction of huge infrastructure projects around the world such as the [[Queen Elizabeth Olympic Park]] in London, [[Disneyland Shanghai]] and some of the terminals at [[Heathrow Airport]] to name a few.\n{{Clear}}\n\n==Media==\n\n===Radio===\n[[Tipp FM]] is a local radio station for the county of Tipperary. It has its main office in Clonmel. In 2019, Tippfm had over 69,000 listeners tuning in every week, increasing its marketshare to 35% [http://tippfm.com/featured-2/tipp-fm-records-significant-increase-listenership-figures/]. It broadcasts on FM, on 95.3, 97.1, 103.3 and 103.9. The Clonmel transmitter broadcasts on 97.1&nbsp;MHz.\n\n===Print===\nClonmel is home to three newspapers: two [[broadsheet]]s and one [[tabloid (newspaper format)|tabloid]] free sheet.\n''The Nationalist'', founded in 1890, is a Clonmel-based broadsheet newspaper that appears weekly, covering both Clonmel town and South Tipperary. It has a circulation of 14,375.<ref>[http://www.ilevel.ie/media-blog/print/10820-irish-regional-newspaper-circulations-july-december-2010 ilevel.ie|Irish Regional Newspaper Circulation Jan June 2010]</ref> It was formed to represent the views of the nationalist community in Tipperary, which led to the first editor being jailed under the [[Coercion Act]] on charges that he had intimidated a cattle dealer for taking a farm from which tenants had been evicted.<ref>[http://www.regionalnewspapers.ie/paperview.php?id=30 regionalnewspapers.ie] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120314043417/http://www.regionalnewspapers.ie/paperview.php?id=30 |date=14 March 2012 }}</ref> It is now run by [[Johnston Press]].\n\nAlso owned by Johnston Press is ''South Tipp Today'', a free tabloid newspaper with a circulation of 20,500 founded in 1995. It is  delivered door-to-door in some areas, and available in local shops across South Tipperary. It is very popular, fondly referred to as the 'small paper' by its readers, and covers news, entertainment, local notes and lifestyle.\n\n''The Sporting Press'' is published and printed in Clonmel, it covers news related to the [[Greyhound racing|greyhound community]] in Ireland. It has a circulation of 7,500.<ref>[http://www.medialive.ie/Magazines/Sport/greypres.html Greyhound Press]\tJournal subscription required medialive.ie  {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20071211071525/http://www.medialive.ie/Magazines/Sport/greypres.html |date=11 December 2007 }}</ref>\n\nThe short-lived ''Premier People'' was launched in Clonmel in October 2010. It was a weekly (tabloid) freesheet with a focus on news, local notes and sports and was published on Tuesday evenings. It was delivered door-to-door in Clonmel and to all shops in South Tipperary. It was founded by Ann Commins, who co-founded ''South Tipp Today''. ''Premier People'' ceased publishing in 2011.<ref>[http://clonmelonline.com/2010/10/the-premier-people/ clonmelonline.com]</ref>\n\nThe ''Tipperary Free Press'' was established in 1826 by the future first catholic Lord Mayor of Clonmel, John Hackett, following a meeting of the Clonmel Corporation.  It was proposed that a Liberal and Independent newspaper should be in circulation in the district and Councillor Hackett, having been a printer and bookbinder in the town for some years, stepped forward to take on the task.   The successful newspaper with a circulation of 45,650 in 1829 was an influential and popular voice in supporting liberal causes, yet it was labelled as radical.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=|first=|date=1830|title=Article IV - The Leeds Mercury; The Manchester Guardian.|url=|journal=The Westminster Review|volume= 12|pages=82|via=}}</ref>  Its primary intention was to be ''<nowiki/>'The voice of the common people''' and played a highly prominent role in the quest for [[Catholic emancipation|Catholic Emancipation]] as advocated by [[Daniel O'Connell]].  Hackett was sued for libel on multiple occasions for his [[caricature]]s of political rivals.  Printed on O'Connell Street bi-weekly, it circulated counties Tipperary, Waterford, Kilkenny, Cork and Limerick.  In its later years it assumed a Catholic-Whig political leaning.  Printing ceased when it was acquired by the ''Tipperary Independent'' (1882-1906) in 1883.\n\n== Culture ==\n\n=== Museums and Galleries ===\n[[File:Cluain Meala (Clonmel), The Main Guard - geograph.org.uk - 260570.jpg|thumb|[[Main Guard (Clonmel)|The Main Guard]]]]\nTipperary County Museum tells the history of [[County Tipperary]] from the [[Stone Age]] to the present. It is also host to many special exhibitions each year. It is the first custom built county museum in Ireland.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.southtippheritage.ie/en/Heritage%20Centres/|title=South Tipperary Co Museum|publisher=South Tipperary Heritage \u2013 S.Tipp. County Council|accessdate=28 June 2009}}{{dead link|date=November 2010}}</ref>\n\nThe [[Main Guard (Clonmel)|Main Guard]] was a civic building until 1810 when it was converted to shops. During recent restoration, some of its sandstone columns were found to have been 'reclaimed' from the now demolished abbey of [[Inislounaght Abbey|Inislounaght]] at [[Marlfield, Clonmel|Marlfield]]. It has been used in the past as a [[Tholsel]] or office to collect tolls, duties and customs dues, a place for civic gatherings and as a court. It now houses an exhibition showing the historic development of Clonmel, including a model of the town as it appeared in the 13th century.\n\nThe South Tipperary Arts Centre opened in 1996. The Arts Centre hosts around 12 exhibitions per year and a variety of art classes for adults and children. As well as presenting a range of visual arts exhibitions in the main gallery space, the centre also host events such as music, performance, poetry readings and dance. The centre has a spacious upstairs studio which is used for short term exhibitions & screenings, as well as for a variety of classes and workshops. It is also a rehearsal space for theatre, dance, music, and is available for meetings and seminars.\n\n=== Theatre and cinema ===\nThe White Memorial Theatre building is a former Weslyan/[[Methodist]] Chapel and was designed and built by local architect [[William Tinsley (architect)|William Tinsley]] in 1843.<ref name=\"Shee & Watson\">{{cite book|last=Shee|first=Elizabeth|title=Clonmel: An Architectural Guide|year=1975|publisher=An Taisce|isbn=978-0-903693-02-8|pages=39|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=mQyspwAACAAJ&dq=clonmel+an+architectural+guide+shee&hl=en&sa=X&ei=8eoxT-GCOoKDhQfFncCOBQ&ved=0CDEQ6AEwAA|author2=Sydney John Watson|accessdate=8 February 2012}}</ref> The building was purchased in 1975 by St. Mary's Choral Society,<ref>[http://www.stmaryschoralsociety.com/homepage.html stmaryschoralsociety.com<!-- Bot generated title -->] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090330063311/http://www.stmaryschoralsociety.com/homepage.html |date=30 March 2009 }}</ref> who put on an average of 2 shows a year in the building. The building also host shows by the Stage Craft Youth Theatre group and special event during the year.\n\nClonmel has a vibrant youth arts sector. Stagecraft Youth Theatre was founded in 1998 by current Artistic Director Shane Dempsey. Stagecraft provides training for young actors in all aspects of theatre practise. Stagecraft is renowned for producing vibrant work in a fun child centred environment. Stagecraft is one of Ireland's largest youth theatre's and is affiliated to NAYD. They have recently staged works by Alex Jones, Enda Walsh, Hannah Burke, Jack Thorne and Moira Buffini.\n\nIn 2011 Shane Dempsey founded The Hub, a 45-seat studio theatre in Albert Street. The Hub is home to Stagecraft.\n\nThe [[Ward Anderson|IMC]], with five screens and located on Kickham Street, is the town's only remaining cinema.<ref>[http://www.omniplex.ie/cinema/cinema/clonmel Clonmel | Omniplex Cinemas, Ireland \u2013 Book Movie Tickets Now<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref> Several other cinemas formerly operated in the town including the Ritz, which opened in 1940<ref>{{cite web|url=http://two.archiseek.com/2009/1939-ritz-cinema-athlone-co-westmeath/|title=1939 \u2013 Ritz Cinema, Athlone, Co. Westmeath|year=2010|publisher=Archiseek|accessdate=8 July 2010}}</ref> and was located on the site of the present [[Irish League of Credit Unions|Credit Union]]. The first cinema in the town opened in January 1913 as the Clonmel Cinema Theatre, soon to be renamed the Clonmel Electric Picture Palace. It was located at the rear of No. 35 Gladstone Street. It was soon followed by John Magner's Theatre at the Mall, which burned to the ground in 1919, to be re-built in 1921 with an increased capacity of over a thousand seats. It was eventually named the Regal Theatre and remodelled as an 850-seat theatre, which finally closed in 2001.<ref>[http://cinematreasures.org/theater/852/ cinematreasures.org]</ref> It was in the Regal Theatre where the tenor [[Frank Patterson]] made his stage debut.<ref>[http://www.rte.ie/ten/2001/0219/clonmel.html rte.ie] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20121102095105/http://www.rte.ie/ten/2001/0219/clonmel.html |date=2 November 2012 }}</ref> The Oisin, in O'Connell Street, was of a similar scale and was also built in 1921. It was on the site of the present day [[Heatons]] but burned to the ground in 1965. The last film to be shown there was ''[[A Patch of Blue]]''.<ref>{{cite book\n|last=O'Donnell\n|first=Sean\n|title=Clonmel 1900\u20131932: A History\n|url=https://books.google.com/?id=00CFPgAACAAJ&dq=clonmel+1900-1932\n|accessdate=8 July 2010\n|year=2009\n|publisher=BPR Publishers\n|isbn=978-0-9562139-0-7\n|pages=139 to 146}}</ref>\n\n=== Festivals ===\n[[File:Community Park.jpg|thumb|alt=Street Performance|Street Performance at Clonmel Junction Festival 2004]]\n[[File:Parnell St Clonmel Busking.JPG|thumb|Mitchell Street, during the Busking Festival in 2014]]\nFor nine days from the first week-end of July, the town hosts the annual [[Clonmel Junction Festival]]. It consists of a mix of [[street theatre]], rock, [[Music of Ireland#Traditional|traditional]] and [[world music]]. Several international acts visit the festival each year. In the last few years, young local bands have also had an opportunity to showcase their talents. Children from local schools and [[Community organization|community groups]] are encouraged to participate with support from local artists.\n\nClonmel is home to the International Film Festival Ireland, which focuses on independent films. Its inaugural event was during September 2009<ref>[https://archive.is/20120903165147/http://www.nationalist.ie/the/Clonmel-to-host-international-film.5419884.jp Clonmel to host international film festival| The Nationalist, 4 July 2009 ]</ref> and ran for five days. It has become an annual event, occurring every September.<ref>{{cite web| title=International Film Festival Ireland \u2013 Official Website| work=southtippfilm.com| url=http://www.southtippfilm.com/| accessdate=5 April 2012| archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120314234537/http://www.southtippfilm.com/| archive-date=14 March 2012| url-status=dead| df=dmy-all}}</ref> The 2010 event expanded to include a Youth Film Festival, that showcased locally made short films.<ref>[https://archive.is/20120904233650/http://www.nationalist.ie/clonmel/Film-festival-visitors-34blown-away34.6543599.jp Film festival visitors \"blown away\" by warm welcome| ''The Nationalist'', 4 July 2009 ]</ref>\n\nThe Clonmel Busking festival runs for four days every August. It provides free music events during the day in Clonmel town centre, while at night a number a concerts take place in various venues throughout the town.<ref>[http://www.clonmelbuskingfestival.com/#!about-us/c1se Clonmel Busking Festival] \u2013 official website</ref>\n\n=== Music ===\n[[Banna Chluain Meala]] (literally translating as 'Clonmel band') was founded in 1971. Originally a brass band, Banna Chluain Meala later developed as a brass and reed band, which included concert, marching and fieldshow performances.  The band also has a colour guard section which enhances marching and fieldshow performances. The total complement of the band has ranged from 100 to 150 members throughout the years.  The band has travelled widely abroad to the United Kingdom, the Netherlands, France, Italy and Chicago in the United States of America and represented Ireland at an International Festival in Cheb in the Czech Republic in 2004 to celebrate the new entrants to the European Union.  Banna Chluain Meala is one of Ireland's most honoured bands.  They hold concert band championship titles on national and international levels.  As a marching band they have had unparalleled success nationally, being crowned IMBA Irish champions in the highest division on twelve occasions (1991, 1995, 1996, 1997, 1998, 1999, 2006, 2007, 2009, 2010, 2011, 2015).  They have also had success abroad, most notably as Open Class champions at the British Youth Band Championships at Wembley in 1994.\n\nClonmel has hosted the Irish traditional music festival, the [[Fleadh Cheoil]], on five occasions from 1992\u201394 inclusive, and again in 2003 and 2004.\n\nOne of the better-known songs concerning Clonmel is \"The Gaol of Cluain Meala,\" a translation from the turn of the 19th century by a Cork man, [[Jeremiah Joseph Callanan]], of the traditional [[Irish language|Irish-language]] song \"Pr\u00edos\u00fan Chluain Meala\".<ref>Lyrics and info. on [http://www.searcs-web.com/anon2.html ''The Gaol of Cl\u00faain Meala''] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120215143540/http://www.searcs-web.com/anon2.html |date=15 February 2012 }}.  The original can be found at: http://songsinirish.com/priosun-chluain-meala-lyrics/ \"Pr\u00edos\u00fan Chluain Meala\".</ref> It was revived by the celebrated balladeer [[Luke Kelly]] in the 1960s. The narrator in the Irish republican song \"[[Galtee Mountain Boy]]\" farewells Clonmel in the song. The song was written by Patsy Halloran from Clonmel.<ref>http://www.songdocs.com/GalteeMountainBoy.doc</ref>\n\nMusic venues in Clonmel include The Piper Inn, famous for hosting a show by Irish rock legends [[Thin Lizzy]].\n\n===Clonmel in literature===\n''Vertue rewarded, or The Irish princess'' (1693), one of the earliest [[romance novel]]s written in the English language, tells the story of \"Merinda\" from High Street, Clonmel and a [[Williamite]] officer stationed in the town during the [[Jacobite War in Ireland|Jacobite war]].<ref>{{cite journal|last=McDermott |first=Hubert |title=      * Vertue Rewarded: The First Anglo-Irish Novel|journal=Studies: An Irish Quarterly Review|publisher= Irish Province of the Society of Jesus |volume= 75|issue=  298 (Summer 1986)|pages=  177\u2013185 (9 pages)|year=1986|jstor=30090731}}</ref>\n\n[[Raymond Chandler]]'s 1939 novel ''[[The Big Sleep]]'' features Rusty Regan as a main character: \"A big curly-headed Irishman from Clonmel, with sad eyes and a smile as wide as Wilshire Boulevard.\"<ref>{{cite book|last=Chandler|first=Raymond|title=The Big Sleep|publisher=Penguin|edition=1992|pages=10|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=fLgrAQAAIAAJ&dq=%22the+big+sleep%22&q=clonmel#search_anchor|accessdate=30 June 2011|year=1992}}</ref>\n\n[[Charles Kickham]]'s 1873 novel ''Knocknagow'' had two main characters modeled off Clonmel locals.  These were his cousins, Dr T.J Crean Sr  as ''\"Arthur O'Conner\"'' and his wife Clara Crean (n\u00e9e Kickham) as ''\"Mary Kearney\",'' who both lived on Queen Street at the time.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://humphrysfamilytree.com/Kickham/dr.thomas.crean.html|title=Crean, Dr. Thomas Crean|last=Mark|first=Humphrys|date=|website=Humphrys Family Tree|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=April 8, 2020}}</ref>\n\n== Sport ==\n{{More citations needed section|date=March 2010}}\n\n=== Association Football ===\nClonmel is home to Clonmel Celtic, Old Bridge, Wilderness Rovers, Redmondstown and Clonmel Town who play in the TSDL League.\n\n===Athletics===\nClonmel is home to Clonmel Athletic Club.\n\n=== Rugby ===\nClonmel Rugby Club plays in the All Ireland League, Division 2C. The rugby club was founded in 1892. In 1990 the club opened their new club House coinciding with the first ever [[Soviet Union national rugby union team|Soviet Union rugby team]] visit to Ireland. In their centenary year, 1992, they hosted [[London Irish|London Irish RFC]] against [[Shannon RFC]] in a memorable game played at the club grounds. Clonmel won the Munster Junior Cup for the first time in its 122-year history in 2014 and followed that up with a Munster Junior League (Division 1) title and the Munster Junior Challenge Cup in the 2015 season.\n\n=== Cricket ===\nClonmel's cricket club plays teams in the Munster Cricket Union Senior 2 and Senior 3 leagues. The cricket club currently fields 1 adult teams and 2 youth teams. All play their home games in the Presentation Convent Field. Clonmel's cricket Club was originally started by a group of friends who originally played the game socially, however the club has been playing competitive cricket for the last 20 years.\n\n=== Horse Racing and Coursing ===\nClonmel is noted in [[greyhound]] circles for being the home of the annual National [[Hare Coursing]] meeting in early February at [[Clonmel Racecourse]] located in the Powerstown area of the town. Also Included in this event is the Ladies' International Open Meeting and the coursing derby. At this time each year, Clonmel's population is swollen by a large influx of sports people from Ireland, the UK, and from as far afield as Australia, New Zealand, the United States and the Middle East.\n\n=== Rowing and boat building ===\nClonmel has two clubs associated with recreational activity on the river Suir, both of which are based in Irishtown.\n\n====Clonmel Rowing Club (CRC)====\nClonmel Rowing Club (CRC), was founded in 1869 and is one of the oldest sporting clubs in the town. It is located on Moor's Island, on the [[Suir]], about 500 meters west of the town centre. The club colours are Royal Blue and White. Sporting success in the early 1900s culminated in the winning of the Senior Men's 'eight' championships in 1920. The club is affectionately known locally as \"The Island\". In winter, training takes place on a 4-mile stretch of the river to the west of the town, from the clubhouse to [[Knocklofty, Clonmel|Knocklofty]] bridge. In the summer months this stretch is reduced to 2 miles as far as Sandybanks, near [[Marlfield, Clonmel|Marlfield]] village.\n\nFlooding has become a perennial problem, especially noticeable in recent years. The flow becomes so fast that rowing in January is not possible on this part of the Suir. Within a 25-mile radius there are two locations where the club can still train satisfactorily, [[Cappoquin]] and [[Fiddown]].\n\nCRC has a newly constructed, purpose built boat house since 1979, with boat storage on the ground floor. Upstairs are two [[Squash (sport)|squash]] courts, a function hall and dressing rooms. Currently one squash court is being used as the gym.\n\nIn the new millennium, the club's veterans are still competing strongly. Women's rowing in Clonmel has developed culminating in Junior Women's 'double [[scull]]' and Junior women's 'eight' championship wins in 2003 and 2005.\n\n==== Workmen's Boat Club ====\nThe Workmen's Boat Club was established in 1883. The property was leased from the Bagwell estate until 1999, when it was finally purchased by the club. One of the major undertakings of the club in recent years has been the restoration of the historic racing craft ''Cruiskeen'', which was built in the 1840s by GAA founder member [[Maurice Davin]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.rte.ie/radio1/seascapes/1173971.html |title=Seascapes News Summary \u2013 26th November 2007 |publisher=RT\u00c9 |accessdate=4 September 2009 |date=27 November 2007 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080503075025/http://www.rte.ie/radio1/seascapes/1173971.html |archivedate=3 May 2008 }}</ref> The project, outsourced to 'Conservation | Letterfrack', took several years of meticulous cleaning, treatment and repair and the 38&nbsp;ft./11.6m timber boat is now on permanent display in the County Museum, Clonmel.<ref>{{cite book|last=Marine Committee of the Heritage Council|author2=Sven Habermann|title=The Future of Maritime and Inland Waterways Collections|editor=Eleanor Flegg|publisher=The Heritage Council|year=2007|isbn=1-901137-99-6|url=http://www.heritagecouncil.ie/fileadmin/user_upload/Publications/Marine/Maritime_Collect_Proceedings.pdf|display-authors=etal|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110927173626/http://www.heritagecouncil.ie/fileadmin/user_upload/Publications/Marine/Maritime_Collect_Proceedings.pdf|archivedate=27 September 2011|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\n=== GAA Clubs ===\nClonmel is home to several [[Gaelic Athletic Association]] (GAA) clubs. [[Clonmel \u00d3g GAA|Clonmel \u00d3g]] the most recently established GAA club in the town was set up in 1984 and it competes in the senior division only 31 years after being formed.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.clonmelog.ie/|title=Clonmel Og|year=2009|publisher=Clonmel Og|accessdate=16 March 2010|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090821110441/http://www.clonmelog.ie/|archivedate=21 August 2009|df=dmy-all}}</ref> [[Moyle Rovers GAA]] club is just outside the town and has been a dominant force in recent decades.\n\n[[Clonmel Commercials]], the 2016 Munster Football Club champions, are based in the town, on the Western Road. They reached the semi-finals of the 2015-16 All Ireland Football Club championships, losing out to Ballyboden St. Endas, who would go on to win the championship. Sister club, [[St. Mary's Hurling Club]], are also located on Western Road.\n\n==Education==\n\n===Primary schools===\n[[File:St. Mary's Parochial School (Model School), Clonmel.jpg|thumb|right|St. Mary's Parochial School]]\n* [[Gaelscoil Chluain Meala]] has around 200<ref>[http://www.education.ie/panels/foundepl.jsp?page=3&educator2=Primary+Schools&pcategory=10917&language=EN&county=Tipperary+S.R.&educator=Primary+Schools&ecategory=12016&roll_no=&Submit=Submit Primary Schools] education.ie</ref> students. Located at Irishtown and originally the Free School, the building was designed by two pupils of the renowned architect [[John Nash (architect)|John Nash]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.buildingsofireland.ie/niah/search.jsp?type=record&county=TS&regno=22116030|title=National Inventory of Architectural Heritage \u2013 Tipperary South|year=2010|publisher=Department of the Environment, Heritage and Local Government.|accessdate=3 June 2010}}</ref> It was for a number of years the offices of South Tipperary County Council.\n* [[St Mary's Parochial School, Clonmel]], also known as the Model School, traces its roots to the Incorporated Society School of 1832. It is located on the Western Road. (''[[Church of Ireland]]'')\n*St Oliver's [[National school (Ireland)|national school]] was founded in 1982.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.education.ie/insreports/report1_19645E.htm|title=Whole School Evaluation REPORT St. Oliver Plunkett's NS Clonmel, County Tipperary Uimhir rolla:  19645E|date=October 2009|publisher=Department of Education and Science|accessdate=15 January 2011}}</ref> It is situated at Heywood Road.\n* St.Mary's CBS is located in Irishtown directly beside the Gaelscoil.\n* St.Peter and Paul's CBS.\n* Sisters of Charity Girls School.\n* Presentation Primary School.\n\n===Secondary schools===\n* [[Presentation Secondary School, Clonmel|Presentation Convent]], for girls, (Roman Catholic)\n* Loreto Convent, for girls, (Roman Catholic)\n* [[CBS High School Clonmel|CBS High School]], for boys, (Roman Catholic)\n* [[Gaelchol\u00e1iste Ch\u00e9itinn]], co-educational. Part of the [[Clonmel Central Technical Institute]]. Established in 2004,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.cti-clonmel.ie/miscellaneous/newsletters/edition03.pdf |title='Name Change Goes Ahead' |publisher=VEC |page=1 |date=2 June 2004 |accessdate=23 May 2011 }}{{dead link|date=June 2017 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.cti-clonmel.ie/miscellaneous/newsletters/welcomeletter.pdf |title=Gaelchol\u00e1iste Ch\u00e9itinn |publisher=VEC |page=1 |date=25 June 2004 |accessdate=23 May 2011 }}{{dead link|date=June 2017 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref> the school teaches through the medium of Irish. It was established as an autonomous school within the [[Vocational Education Committee]] system in response to a demand for second-level education through the medium of Irish.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.tipperarystar.ie/3582/Gael-Choliste-Chitinn--fostering.1399863.jp |archive-url=https://archive.is/20120914122238/http://www.tipperarystar.ie/3582/Gael-Choliste-Chitinn--fostering.1399863.jp |url-status=dead |archive-date=14 September 2012 |title=Gael Chol\u00e1iste Ch\u00e9itinn \u2013 fostering the Irish language of a distinctive nation |date=24 March 2006 |publisher=Tipperary Star |accessdate=3 June 2010 }}</ref>\n* [[Col\u00e1iste Chluain Meala]], co-educational. Formerly known as ''The [[Clonmel Central Technical Institute]] Secondary School''<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.cti-clonmel.ie/miscellaneous/newsletters/edition02.pdf |title=The Central Technical Institute Newsletter |date=29 March 2004 |publisher=VEC |page=1 |accessdate=3 June 2010 }}{{dead link|date=June 2017 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref> which traces its history back to 1842.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.cti-clonmel.ie/centraltechnicalinstitute/history.shtml |title=The Central Technical Institute Website |publisher=VEC |accessdate=23 May 2011 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090621220620/http://www.cti-clonmel.ie/centraltechnicalinstitute/history.shtml |archivedate=21 June 2009 }}</ref> Under the control of the local [[Education and Training Board]].\n* CTI [[Senior College]], co-educational. Part of the [[Clonmel Central Technical Institute]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.cti-clonmel.ie/|title=The Central Technical Institute Website|publisher=VEC|accessdate=23 May 2011}}</ref> and under the control of the local [[Education and Training Board]]. There is an official website listing PLC courses.\n\n===Third level===\nClonmel is home to one [[List of higher education institutions in the Republic of Ireland|third-level college]], [[Limerick Institute of Technology|LIT]]. The Clonmel Campus of LIT offers courses in Business, Creative Multimedia, Digital Animation Production and Marketing with Languages. The Creative Multimedia & Digital Animation Production degrees are operated under the LIT Limerick School of Art and Design. The LIT Clonmel campus is located along the Clonmel Inner Relief Road, but it is proposed that it will move to a new location within the town centre in the future.\n\n===Training===\nClonmel Youth Training Entreprises Limited was established in 1984 by voluntary and business people, who saw the need to tackle the growing issue of unemployment and the related consequences of early school leavers in Clonmel.\n\nToday the primary objective of helping young people to become mature, confident and competent young adults, ready for the world of work, still holds true.\n\n==Transport==\n\n===Roads===\nClonmel is located on the [[N24 road (Ireland)|N24]], the national primary roadway that links the cities of Limerick and Waterford. The N24 westbound connects Clonmel to junction 10 of the [[Cork (city)|Cork]] to [[Dublin]] [[M8 motorway (Ireland)|M8 motorway]], while eastbound it links the town with [[Kilkenny]] via the [[N76 road (Ireland)|N76]].\n\n[[Charles Bianconi]], onetime mayor of the town, ran his pioneering public transport system of horse-drawn carriages from Clonmel.\n\n===Rail===\n[[Clonmel railway station]] opened on 1 May 1852.<ref>{{cite web | title=Clonmel station | work=Railscot \u2013 Irish Railways | url=http://www.railscot.co.uk/Ireland/Irish_railways.pdf |format=PDF| accessdate=7 September 2007}}</ref> Today there are two trains daily to [[Waterford]] via [[Carrick on Suir]], and two to [[Limerick Junction]] via [[Cahir]] and [[County Tipperary|Tipperary]] which has main-line connections to [[Dublin]]. There is no Sunday service.\n\n===Waterways===\nThe River Suir had been made navigable to Clonmel from 1760 when completion of the [[River Suir Navigation]] in the 19th century allowed large vessels to reach the town's [[quay]]s.\n\n==People associated with Clonmel==\n* [[Anne Anderson (diplomat)|Anne Anderson]] (born 1952), was Ireland's  first female Ambassador to the United States of America, United Nations, France, Monaco and European Union, born in Clonmel.\n* [[Bonaventura Baron]] (1610\u20131696), a distinguished Franciscan humanist, philosopher and writer was born in Clonmel.\n* [[Charles Bianconi]] (1786\u20131875), one-time mayor of Clonmel, ran his pioneering public transport system of horse-drawn carriages from Clonmel\n* [[George Borrow]] (1803\u20131881), [[Multilingualism|polyglot]], [[ethnologist]] of the [[Romani people]] and author of ''[[Lavengro]]'', in which he briefly writes of his time in Clonmel, lived here in 1815\n* [[Francis Bryan]] (1490\u20131550), English courtier and diplomat during the reign of [[Henry VIII of England|Henry VIII]], died in Clonmel in 1550<ref>[https://books.google.com/books?id=f3oPx3711Z0C&pg=PA47&dq=%22governor+general%22+ireland++francis+bryan&cd=1#v=onepage&q=%22governor%20general%22%20ireland%20%20francis%20bryan&f=false ''The Spear and the Spindle''] p48</ref>\n* [[Austin Carroll]] (1835\u20131909), Irish Catholic nun and writer\n* [[Thomas Chamney]], Irish athlete who ran 800m in Beijing Olympics in 2008\n* [[William J. Duane]] (1780\u20131865), American politician and lawyer from [[Pennsylvania]], was born in Clonmel.\n* [[Dave Foley (rugby union)|Dave Foley]] is a professional rugby union player\n* [[Sarah Pim Grubb]] (1746\u20131832), Quaker businesswoman, wife of John Grubb, died in Clonmel\n* [[Vincent Hanley]] (1954\u20131987), a pioneering Irish radio DJ and television presenter, nicknamed \"Fab Vinny\". He worked mainly for [[Raidi\u00f3 Teilif\u00eds \u00c9ireann]] and was the first Irish celebrity to die from an AIDS-related illness<ref>[http://www.rte.ie/tv/theafternoonshow/2008/1211/giftguide.html Vincent Hanley, AIDs related death \u2013 charity appeal]</ref>\n* [[Sir Lionel Milman, 7th Baronet]] (1877\u20131962), Anglo-Irish first-class cricketer and British Army officer\n* [[Fred Murray]], former professional football player, now personal masseuse for Foo Fighters member Dave Grohl\n* [[Vivian Murray]], businessman\n* [[Pat O'Callaghan]] was an Irish athlete and [[Athletics at the 1928 Summer Olympics \u2013 Men's hammer throw|1928 Olympic gold medalist]]\n* [[M\u00edche\u00e1l \u00d3 S\u00failleabh\u00e1in]] (1950\u20132018), an Irish musician, held Professorship of Music at the Irish World Music Centre of the University of Limerick\n* [[Frank Patterson]] (1938\u20132000), one of Ireland's most famous [[tenors]], was native to the town\n* [[Ramsay Weston Phipps]] (1838\u20131923), military historian, born in Clonmel, lived there off and on throughout his life\n* [[Rozanna Purcell]], model and Miss Universe Ireland 2010\n* [[Adi Roche]], co-founder of [[Chernobyl Children's Project International]] and [[1997 Irish presidential election|1997]] candidate for the [[President of Ireland|Irish Presidency]]\n* [[Andrea Roche]], best known Irish model and Miss Ireland 1997\n* [[Symon Semeonis]], or Simon Fitzsimons, was a 14th-century Franciscan friar who left Clonmel in 1323 on pilgrimage to the [[Holy Land]]. The account of his \"Itinerary\" is preserved in a manuscript in the Library of Corpus Christi College, Cambridge\n* [[Laurence Sterne]] (1713\u201368), author of ''[[The Life and Opinions of Tristram Shandy, Gentleman]]'', was born in the town, though his family returned to England soon after\n* [[Anthony Trollope]] (1815\u20131852), a noted author, worked in the town for a period\n* [[Stephen White (Jesuit)|Stephen White]] (1575\u20131646) was an Irish Jesuit, historian and antiquarian born in Clonmel, who wrote about the early Irish saints\n\n{{Historical populations\n| state = collapsed\n|1821|15590\n|1831|15134\n|1841|13505\n|1851|11589\n|1861|11646\n|1871|10112\n|1881|9325\n|1891|8480\n|1901|10167\n|1911|10209\n|1926|9056\n|1936|9391\n|1946|9857\n|1951|10471\n|1956|11134\n|1961|11087\n|1966|11457\n|1971|12291\n|1981|14808\n|1986|15517\n|1991|15562\n|1996|16182\n|2002|16910\n|2006|17008\n|2011|17908\n|2016|17140\n| footnote=<ref>Sources: [http://www.cso.ie/census CSO] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20050309005718/http://www.cso.ie/census/ |date=9 March 2005 }} and [http://www.histpop.org/ohpr/servlet/ HistPop]. Allowance has not been made for periodic changes to borough boundaries.\n</ref>\n}}\n\n==Sister towns==\nClonmel is [[town twinning|twinned]] with several places:\n\n<!-- NOTE ON FLAG ICONS : Please do not add flag icons to this section. There is a longstanding convention to avoid flag icons (per MOS:FLAG and WP:CON) because it causes too many edit wars over whether national or regional flags should be used. -->\n{|\n|-\n| valign=\"top\" |\n* [[Costa Masnaga]], Lombardy, Italy.\n* [[Gangi, Sicily]], Italy.\n* [[Reading, Berkshire|Reading]], England.<ref name=\"Reading twinning\">{{cite web|url=http://www.reading.gov.uk/council/town-twinning/ |title=Reading \u2013 Town Twinning |accessdate=14 July 2013 |work=Reading Borough Council |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130509063652/http://www.reading.gov.uk/council/town-twinning/ |archivedate=9 May 2013 |df=dmy }}</ref>\n| valign=\"top\" |\n* [[Eysines]], [[Aquitaine]], France.\n* [[Trofaiach]], [[Styria]], Austria.\n* [[Peoria, Illinois]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://dublin.usembassy.gov/sister_cities.html |title=sister cities |last=U.S. Embassy Dublin |publisher=U.S. Department of State |accessdate=6 August 2009 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090802225732/http://dublin.usembassy.gov/sister_cities.html |archivedate=2 August 2009 |df=dmy }}</ref>\n* [[Roeselare]], Belgium\n|}\n\n==See also==\n* [[Clonmel Borstal]]\n* [[Ferryhouse|St Joseph's Industrial School, Ferryhouse]]\n* [[Grange, County Tipperary]]\n* [[List of towns and villages in the Republic of Ireland|List of towns and villages in Ireland]]\n* [[Market Houses in the Republic of Ireland|Market Houses in Ireland]]\n* [[Siege of Clonmel]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|colwidth=30em}}\n* [https://archive.org/details/historyclonmel00burkgoog ''History of Clonmel''] William P. Burke 1907 from [[Internet Archive]].\n* [https://archive.org/details/anglerinireland00biltgoog/page/n31 <!-- pg=14 quote=clonmel. --> Observations on fishing and other 'native fauna', Clonmel, 1833]\n* [https://books.google.com/books?id=wiZIAAAAMAAJ&pg=PR1&lpg=PR1&dq=inglis+ireland+writer&source=web&ots=x0yBuswmya&sig=jwna3PQtxxFGY0-TiwFhrnmSqWQ&hl=en&sa=X&oi=book_result&resnum=9&ct=result#PPA130,M1 From Cahir to Clonmel, 1834]\n* White, James : ''My Clonmel Scrapbook'' : 1995 based on 1907 original {{ISBN|978-1-899003-16-7}}\n* ''The Cistercian Abbeys of Tipperary'' (inc. Inislaunaght founded 1147-8) [https://web.archive.org/web/20120214131357/http://www.fourcourtspress.ie/product.php?intProductID=183 from Four Courts Press] {{ISBN|978-1-85182-380-2}}\n* Watson, Sydney John : ''A Dinner of Herbs: A History of Old Saint Mary's Church, Clonmel'' 1988 {{ISBN|978-0-9513212-0-1}}\n* McGrath,  Br\u00edd (ed.): ''The Minute Book of the Corporation of Clonmel, 1608\u20131649'' : [http://www.irmss.ie/ Irish Manuscripts Commission]  : 2006 :  {{ISBN|978-1-874280-53-8}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category}}\n\n{{County Tipperary}}\n\n[[Category:Clonmel| ]]\n[[Category:County towns in the Republic of Ireland]]\n[[Category:Towns and villages in County Tipperary]]\n[[Category:Boroughs in the Republic of Ireland]]\n[[Category:Iffa and Offa East]]\n", "text_old": "{{other uses}}\n{{EngvarB|date=November 2015}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=November 2015}}\n\n{{Infobox settlement\n|settlement_type        = Town\n|name                   = Clonmel\n|native_name             = {{Pad top italic|Cluain Meala}}\n|image_shield           = Clonmel COA.png\n|shield_size            = 150px\n|motto = ''Fidelis in \u00c6ternum''{{spaces|2}}<small>([[Latin language|Latin]])</small><br />\"Faithful Forever\"\n|pushpin_map            = Ireland\n|pushpin_label_position = right\n|pushpin_map_caption    = Location in Ireland\n|coordinates            = {{coord|52.3539|-7.7116|dim:100000_region:IE|display=inline,title}}\n|blank_name_sec1        = Irish Grid Reference\n|blank_info_sec1        = {{iem4ibx|S199229}}\n|area_total_km2         = 10.5\n|unit_pref              = Metric\n|elevation_m            = 20\n|subdivision_type       = Country\n|subdivision_name       = Ireland\n|subdivision_type1      = [[Provinces of Ireland|Province]]\n|subdivision_name1      = [[Munster]]\n|subdivision_type2      = [[Counties of Ireland|County]]\n|subdivision_name2      = [[County Tipperary]]\n|population_as_of       = 2016\n|population_footnotes   = <ref name=\"sapmap2016\">{{cite web|url =\nhttp://census.cso.ie/sapmap2016/Results.aspx?Geog_Type=ST2016&Geog_Code=64AB345C-A63F-46C4-A2D5-8F5447FCD731#SAPMAP_T1_100 | publisher = [[Central Statistics Office (Ireland)|CSO]] | work = Census 2016 | title = Sapmap Area - Settlements - Clonmel | date = 2016 | accessdate = 12 January 2018 }}</ref>\n|population_total       = 17,140   \n|population_density_km2 = 1,636.4\n|website                =\n|subdivision_type3      = D\u00e1il \u00c9ireann\n|subdivision_name3      = [[Tipperary (D\u00e1il constituency)|Tipperary]]\n|subdivision_type4      = EU Parliament\n|subdivision_name4      = [[South (European Parliament constituency)|South]]\n| area_code_type = [[Telephone numbers in the Republic of Ireland|Telephone area code]]\n| area_code = 052\n| postal_code_type        =[[Eircode]]\n| postal_code             =E91\n|timezone                = [[Western European Time|WET]]\n|utc_offset              = 0\n|timezone_DST            = [[Irish Standard Time|IST]]\n|utc_offset_DST          = +1\n|image_skyline          = Clonmel.jpg\n|image_caption          = The Quays, Clonmel.\n}}\n'''Clonmel''' ({{Irish place name|Cluain Meala|honey meadow}}) is the [[county town]] and largest settlement of [[County Tipperary]], [[Republic of Ireland|Ireland]]. The town is noted in Irish history for its resistance to the [[Cromwellian conquest of Ireland|Cromwellian army]] which sacked the towns of [[Drogheda]] and [[Wexford]]. With the exception of the [[townland]] of Suir Island, most of the borough is situated in the [[Civil parishes in Ireland|civil parish]] of \"St Mary's\"<ref>[https://www.logainm.ie/2335.aspx Placenames Database of Ireland] - St Mary's, Clonmel civil parish</ref> which is part of the ancient [[Barony (Ireland)|barony]] of [[Iffa and Offa East]].\n\n==Population==\nThe 2016 Census used a new boundary created by the [[Central Statistics Office (Ireland)|Central Statistics Office]] (CSO) to define the town of Clonmel and Environs resulting in a population figure of 17,140. This new boundary omitted part of the Clonmel Borough Boundary which the CSO had defined as Legal Town for the 2011 census 11.55&nbsp;km/sq. All of the 2011 census CSO environ in Co Waterford have been omitted as well as parts of CSO Environ of Clonmel in Co Tipperary. The CSO as part of the 11 May 2017 release of data compared their new 2016 CSO boundary with its population of 17,140 with the 2011 CSO Clonmel Environ boundary which is a larger area and had a resulting greater population of 17,908. The CSO are not comparing the same area and are incorrectly recorded a population decline of 768 (-4.3%).\n\nClonmel Borough (CSO Legal Town 2011, 11.55&nbsp;km/sq) had a population of 15,793 in 2011, another 2115 people were in the rural environs of Clonmel comprising Marlfield, Ardgeeha Upper (Cashel Rd), Boherduff (Fethard Rd) in County Tipperary and in [[County Waterford]] the area between the Dungarvan Rd and Mountain Rd.<ref>[http://beyond2020.cso.ie/Census/TableViewer/tableView.aspx?ReportId=109359 C.S.O. Census 2011] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130622071349/http://beyond2020.cso.ie/Census/TableViewer/tableView.aspx?ReportId=109359 |date=22 June 2013 }}</ref>\n\n==Etymology==\nThe name Clonmel is derived from the [[anglicisation]] of the Irish name ''Cluain Meala'' meaning honey meadow or honey vale. It is not clearly known when it got this name; many suppose that it came from the fertility of the soil and the richness of the country in which it is situated.<ref>[https://archive.org/details/historyclonmel00burkgoog History of Clonmel (1907)]</ref>\n\n== History ==\n[[File:Old Saint Marys, Clonmel.jpg|thumb|250px|right|Old St. Mary's Church]]\n\n===Town walls===\nClonmel grew significantly in [[medieval]] times, and many remainders of this period can be found in the town. A small section of the town walls remain in place near [[Old St. Mary's Church (Clonmel)|Old St. Mary's Church]] . This building is one of the main architectural features of the town. It was originally built in the 14th century or earlier but has been reconstructed or renovated on numerous occasions. The church was fortified early in its history, the town being strategically important, initially for the [[Earl of Ormonde (Irish)|Earls of Ormonde]], and later the [[Earl of Kildare]]. Some fortified parts of the church were destroyed or damaged during the [[Cromwellian conquest of Ireland|Cromwellian occupation]]. One of the former entry points into the town is now the site of the 'West Gate', a 19th-century reconstruction of an older structure. There were originally three gates in the walled town, North, East and West \u2013 with the South being protected by the river [[Suir]] and the [[Comeragh Mountains]]. The 'West Gate' is now an open arched entrance on to O'Connell street, the main street of the town.\n\n===Corporation regalia===\nUnder a charter granted by [[James I of England]], Clonmel became a [[Borough|Free Borough]] on 5 July 1608, and the Mayor and officers of the town were granted power to \"name, elect and constitute one Swordbearer and three Sergeants-at-Mace\". The present sword and two silver maces date only from Cromwellian times. The sword, of [[Toledo, Spain|Toledo]] manufacture, was donated by Sir Thomas Stanley in 1656 and displays the Arms and motto of the town. The larger mace is stamped 1663.<ref>{{cite book|last=Burke  |first= William P. |title=History of Clonmel|publisher=N. Harvey & co. for the Clonmel Library Committee|year=1907|pages=[https://archive.org/details/historyclonmel00burkgoog/page/n265 235]\u2013237|url=https://archive.org/details/historyclonmel00burkgoog}}</ref>\n\n===Cromwellian period===\n[[File:Western Tower, Clonmel's Town Wall..jpg|thumb|120px|right|One of the remaining towers of Clonmel's defensive wall]]\n[[File:371 of 'Cromwell in Ireland, a history of Cromwell's Irish Campaign ... with map, plans and illustrations' (11164473114).jpg|thumb|400px|Map of 17th-century Clonmel. Note \"Irishtown\" in the west.]]\n[[Oliver Cromwell]] [[Siege of Clonmel|laid siege to Clonmel]] in May 1650. The walls were eventually breached, but [[Hugh Dubh O'Neill]], the commander of the town's garrison, inflicted heavy losses on the [[New Model Army]] when they tried to storm the breach. That night, O'Neill, deciding that further resistance was hopeless due to a lack of ammunition, led his soldiers and camp followers out of the town under cover of darkness. The story is told that Cromwell became suspicious of O'Neill's desperate situation when a silver bullet was discharged by the townspeople at his troops outside the walls.<ref>{{cite book|last=Curry|first=William|title=The Dublin University Magazine |publisher=William Curry, Jun., and Co.|year=1853|volume=v. 42|url=https://books.google.com/?id=5NoRAAAAYAAJ&pg=PA329&dq=clonmel+%22silver+bullet%22|accessdate=27 June 2009}}</ref> The following morning, 18 May 1650, mayor John White was able to surrender the town on good terms as Cromwell was still unaware of the garrison's escape just hours before. Although feeling deceived, he did not put the inhabitants 'to the sword' as occurred elsewhere.\n\n[[File:Trial of Irish patriots Clonmel.jpg|thumb|left|200px|[[Young Irelanders]] stand trial before [[Francis Blackburne|Justice Blackburne]] at Clonmel, 1848]]\n\n===19th century===\nA permanent military presence was established in the town with the completion of [[Kickham Barracks]] in 1805.<ref>{{cite web|url= http://uccplanningsoc.files.wordpress.com/2012/11/kickham-barracks-development-proposal.pdf|title=The Kickham Army Barracks Development Proposal|publisher=University College Cork|accessdate=11 November 2014}}</ref>\n\nFollowing the failed attempt at rebellion near [[Ballingarry, South Tipperary|Ballingarry]] in 1848, the captured leaders of the [[Young Irelanders]] were brought to Clonmel for trial.<ref>{{cite book|last=McConville|first=Se\u00e1n|title=Irish political prisoners, 1848\u20131922: theatres of war|publisher=Routledge|year=2003|page=42|isbn=978-0-415-21991-4|url=https://books.google.com/?id=rLrsi3hpXIQC&pg=PA42|accessdate=7 July 2009}}</ref> The event was followed with great interest internationally and for its duration brought journalists from around the country and Britain to [[Clonmel Courthouse]]. Standing in the dock in the image opposite are [[Thomas Francis Meagher]], [[Terence MacManus]] and [[Patrick O'Donoghue (Young Irelander)|Patrick O'Donoghue]]. Their co-defendant, [[William Smith O'Brien]] was also sentenced to be [[hanged, drawn and quartered]], the last occasions such a sentence was handed down in Ireland. When delivering the guilty verdict, the foreman of the [[Grand jury#Ireland|Grand Jury]], R.M. Southcote Mansergh, great grandfather of the academic [[Nicholas Mansergh]] stated:\n<blockquote>\nWe earnestly recommend the prisoner to the merciful consideration of the Government, being unanimously of opinion that for many reasons his life should be spared.<ref>{{cite book|last=Mansergh|first=Nicholas|title=Nationalism and independence: selected Irish papers Irish History Series |editor=Diana Mansergh|publisher=Cork University Press|year=1997|isbn=978-1-85918-106-5|url=https://books.google.com/?id=f7OC7YQkFwYC&pg=PA124&dq=%22southcote+mansergh%22&q=%22southcote%20mansergh%22|accessdate=15 August 2009}}</ref>\n</blockquote>\nThe sentences of O'Brien and other members of the [[Irish Confederation]] were eventually commuted to [[Penal transportation|transportation]] for life to [[Van Diemen's Land]]. A conspiracy to rescue the prisoners on 8 November led by [[John O'Leary (Fenian)|John O'Leary]] and [[Philip Gray]] was betrayed, and resulted in the arrest at 'The Wilderness' of seventeen armed rebels led by Gray.<ref>O'Donnell, Sean : [https://books.google.com/books?id=ibJnAAAAMAAJ&q=clonmel+anatomy+of+an+irish+town&dq=clonmel+anatomy+of+an+irish+town&pgis=1 ''Clonmel \u2013 1840\u20131900 Anatomy of an Irish Town''] 1999 {{ISBN|978-0-906602-51-5}} p153</ref>\n\n===20th century===\nClonmel was the location of the foundation of the [[Labour Party (Ireland)|Labour Party]] in 1912 by [[James Connolly]], [[James Larkin]] and [[William O'Brien]] as the political wing of the [[Irish Trades Union Congress]].<ref>[http://www.labour.ie/party/history.html labour.ie]</ref>\n\n===21st century===\nIn November 2015 the town was the location of Ireland's first marriage between two men.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Dalby|first1=James|title=First Same-Sex Marriage Ceremoney Held in Ireland|publisher=New York Times|date=19 November 2015}}</ref>\n\n== Politics and government ==\nClonmel had a Borough Council until 2014. It was one of five Borough Councils in Ireland. It had 12 elected representatives (councillors). John Hackett was the first Mayor and Pat English was the last Mayor of Clonmel Borough Council.\n\nFor local elections in 2014 the District of Cahir-Clonmel elected nine members to [[Tipperary County Council]].\n\n===National===\nClonmel belongs to the [[Tipperary (D\u00e1il constituency)|Tipperary constituency]] which elects five [[Teachta D\u00e1la|TD]]s to [[D\u00e1il \u00c9ireann]] (the Irish Parliament).\n\nIn the 2016 General Election [[Mattie McGrath]] (Independent), [[Michael Lowry]] (Independent), [[Alan Kelly (politician)|Alan Kelly]] ([[Labour Party (Ireland)|Labour Party]]), [[Jackie Cahill]] ([[Fianna F\u00e1il]]) and [[S\u00e9amus Healy]] ([[Workers and Unemployed Action]]) won the five seats.\n\nThe [[2020 Irish General Election]] was supposed to  be postponed due to the sudden death of Independent candidate Marese Skehan [https://www.bbc.com/news/world-europe-51369150]. This was because it was a requirement under the 1992 Electoral Act Section 62. However, Attorney General S\u00e9amus Woulfe advised the Government that the entire general election could be open to a legal challenge if the Tipperary poll did not go ahead. So the election continued on Saturday February 8 along with the rest of the country. It was [[Michael Lowry]] (Independent) elected on the first count winning 18.1% of the first preference votes. [[Mattie McGrath]] (Independent) and [[Martin Browne (politician)|Martin Browne]] ([[Sinn F\u00e9in]]) were elected on the 8th count. While [[Alan Kelly (politician)|Alan Kelly]] ([[Labour Party (Ireland)|Labour Party]]) and [[Jackie Cahill]] ([[Fianna F\u00e1il]]) made it in on the 9th count.[https://www.rte.ie/news/election-2020/results/#/national/tipperary] This still gives Clonmel no sitting TD as town mayor Garret Ahern was not elected. \n{{Clear}}\n\n[[File:A street in Clonmel.jpg|thumb|A street in Clonmel, Ireland]]\n\n==Geography==\nThe town is built in the valley of the [[River Suir]]. It divides the town which is mainly located on the north bank. To the south the town is surround by the [[Comeragh Mountains]] and [[Slievenamon]] to the northeast. To the north, east and west is some of Irelands richest farmland known as the [[Golden Vale]]. The town covers a land area of approximately 11.59km2.\n\n===Climate===\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"width: 50%; margin: 0 auto 0 auto;\"\n|+ '''Climate Table'''\n!\n! Jan\n! Feb\n! Mar\n! Apr\n! May\n! Jun\n! Jul\n! Aug\n! Sep\n! Oct\n! Nov\n! Dec\n!Year\n|-\n! Average daily maximum temperature (\u00b0C)\n| 8\n| 8\n| 10\n| 13\n| 16\n| 18\n| 20\n| 20\n| 18\n| 14\n| 10\n| 8\n| '''14'''\n|-\n! Average daily minimum temperature (\u00b0C)\n| 3\n| 3\n| 4\n| 5\n| 7\n| 10\n| 12\n| 12\n| 10\n| 7\n| 5\n| 4\n| '''7'''\n|-\n! Mean total rainfall (cm)\n| 5.34\n| 4.29\n| 3.84\n| 3.98\n| 3.40\n| 3.72\n| 3.38\n| 4.22\n| 4.33\n| 6.35\n| 5.07\n| 5.03\n| '''52.95'''\n|-\n| colspan=\"15\" style=\"text-align: center;\" | <small>'''Source:''' MSN Weather</small>\n|}\n\n===Flood defences===\nThe [[River Suir]] floods the local area after very heavy rainfalls in the up-river catchment area of 2,173&nbsp;km<sup>2</sup>. The [[Office of Public Works]] (OPW) completed and installed a Flood Forecasting System which has been used since 2007. The flood of 2015 had a flow of 390m<sup>3</sup>/s, 2004 had a flow of 354m<sup>3</sup>/s with the flood of 2000 having a flow of 353m<sup>3</sup>/s. The 2015 flood was the worst since that of 1946, which had seen a flow of 479m<sup>3</sup>/s. Phase 1 of the Clonmel Flood Defence (planned to cope with a [[100-year flood]]) started in 2007. It was scheduled to be completed by late 2009. Phases two and three were completion by 2012. Property omitted from Phase 1 along the convent road were protected in 2014 and the access to the river for the workmans boat club was also raised. \nFlooding of October 2014 was less than a 1\u20135 flood with a flow of 300m<sup>3</sup>/s. As part of a media exercise by the OPW the barrier were all put up.<ref>{{cite web|last1=OPW|title=Office of Public Works \u2013 Flood Defence Management|url=http://www.opw.ie/floodriskmanagement/floodriskmanagementoperations/majorflooddefenceschemes/clonmelflooddefencescheme/#.VFZYAsV_shY|accessdate=2 November 2014|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20141102175128/http://www.opw.ie/floodriskmanagement/floodriskmanagementoperations/majorflooddefenceschemes/clonmelflooddefencescheme/#.VFZYAsV_shY|archivedate=2 November 2014|df=dmy-all}}</ref> The flood defence consists of demountable barriers, walls and earth banks. Flooding occurred at the Gashouse Bridge, Coleville Road, Davis Road, the Quays and the Old Bridge area before the flood defences. Clonmel is not tidal as the tide turns above the [[Glanbia|Miloko]] chocolate crumb factory in [[Carrick-on-Suir]]. Flood waters spill onto the land above Miloko on the [[County Waterford]] side of the river.\n\n==Economy==\n\n===Retail===\nClonmel's main shopping streets are Gladstone Street and O'Connell Street which are home to many national and international retailers such as [[Elverys Sports]], [[Penneys]], [[River Island]], [[Easons]] and [[Lifestyle Sports]] to name a few. More local retailers can be found along the streets branching off from those streets.\n\nThe Showgrounds Shopping Centre built during the [[Celtic Tiger]] can be found only 1&nbsp;km from the town centre. This modern shopping centre built on the towns original show ground, houses retailers such as [[M&S]], [[TKMaxx]], [[Argos]] and [[Golden Discs]].\n\nThe Poppyfield Retail Park is located on the outskirts of the town. It has many stores such as DID Electrical, [[Supervalue]], Maxi Zoo, [[Woodie's DIY|Woodie's]] and World of Wonder. The retail park has food vendors being [[KFC]], [[Costa Coffee]], the Red Herring and Esquires Coffee. There is also a hotel on the site.\n\n===Industry===\n[[File:Bulmers factory clonmel.png|thumb|right|200px|Bulmers cider factory]]\nIn recent times, Clonmel have become home to many large multi-national companies, particularly in the medical area. The two biggest medical companies in the town are [[Abbott Laboratories|Abbott]] and [[Boston Scientific]], both of which manufacture implantable devices. Two other multi-national pharmaceutical companies are [[Merck & Co.]] and Pinewood Healthcare found less than twenty minutes away.\n\nThe town produces many beverages both alcoholic and non-alcoholic. [[Bulmers (Republic of Ireland)|Bulmers]] [[cider]], also known as [[Bulmers (Ireland)|Magners]] outside Ireland, was founded in the town and is still brewed in a new complex {{convert|2|km}} east of the town with orchards surrounding it. The original brewery in the town is set to turn in to a new visitor attraction. Glenpatrick Spring Water bottles still, carbonated and flavoured water from the limestone rocks beneath [[Slievenamon]] for many big supermarket chains in Ireland and the UK such as Tesco and M&S.\n\nClonmel is home to international engineering and construction groups such as [[Kentz]] and Sepam who were both founded in the town. Sepam has helped in the construction of huge infrastructure projects around the world such as the [[Queen Elizabeth Olympic Park]] in London, [[Disneyland Shanghai]] and some of the terminals at [[Heathrow Airport]] to name a few.\n{{Clear}}\n\n==Media==\n\n===Radio===\n[[Tipp FM]] is a local radio station for the county of Tipperary. It has its main office in Clonmel. In 2019, Tippfm had over 69,000 listeners tuning in every week, increasing its marketshare to 35% [http://tippfm.com/featured-2/tipp-fm-records-significant-increase-listenership-figures/]. It broadcasts on FM, on 95.3, 97.1, 103.3 and 103.9. The Clonmel transmitter broadcasts on 97.1&nbsp;MHz.\n\n===Print===\nClonmel is home to three newspapers: two [[broadsheet]]s and one [[tabloid (newspaper format)|tabloid]] free sheet.\n''The Nationalist'', founded in 1890, is a Clonmel-based broadsheet newspaper that appears weekly, covering both Clonmel town and South Tipperary. It has a circulation of 14,375.<ref>[http://www.ilevel.ie/media-blog/print/10820-irish-regional-newspaper-circulations-july-december-2010 ilevel.ie|Irish Regional Newspaper Circulation Jan June 2010]</ref> It was formed to represent the views of the nationalist community in Tipperary, which led to the first editor being jailed under the [[Coercion Act]] on charges that he had intimidated a cattle dealer for taking a farm from which tenants had been evicted.<ref>[http://www.regionalnewspapers.ie/paperview.php?id=30 regionalnewspapers.ie] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120314043417/http://www.regionalnewspapers.ie/paperview.php?id=30 |date=14 March 2012 }}</ref> It is now run by [[Johnston Press]].\n\nAlso owned by Johnston Press is ''South Tipp Today'', a free tabloid newspaper with a circulation of 20,500 founded in 1995. It is  delivered door-to-door in some areas, and available in local shops across South Tipperary. It is very popular, fondly referred to as the 'small paper' by its readers, and covers news, entertainment, local notes and lifestyle.\n\n''The Sporting Press'' is published and printed in Clonmel, it covers news related to the [[Greyhound racing|greyhound community]] in Ireland. It has a circulation of 7,500.<ref>[http://www.medialive.ie/Magazines/Sport/greypres.html Greyhound Press]\tJournal subscription required medialive.ie  {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20071211071525/http://www.medialive.ie/Magazines/Sport/greypres.html |date=11 December 2007 }}</ref>\n\nThe short-lived ''Premier People'' was launched in Clonmel in October 2010. It was a weekly (tabloid) freesheet with a focus on news, local notes and sports and was published on Tuesday evenings. It was delivered door-to-door in Clonmel and to all shops in South Tipperary. It was founded by Ann Commins, who co-founded ''South Tipp Today''. ''Premier People'' ceased publishing in 2011.<ref>[http://clonmelonline.com/2010/10/the-premier-people/ clonmelonline.com]</ref>\n\nThe ''Tipperary Free Press'' was established in 1826 by the future first catholic Lord Mayor of Clonmel, John Hackett, following a meeting of the Clonmel Corporation.  It was proposed that a Liberal and Independent newspaper should be in circulation in the district and Councillor Hackett, having been a printer and bookbinder in the town for some years, stepped forward to take on the task.   The successful newspaper with a circulation of 45,650 in 1829 was an influential and popular voice in supporting liberal causes, yet it was labelled as radical.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=|first=|date=1830|title=Article IV - The Leeds Mercury; The Manchester Guardian.|url=|journal=The Westminster Review|volume=Volume 12|pages=82|via=}}</ref>  Its primary intention was to be ''<nowiki/>'The voice of the common people''' and played a highly prominent role in the quest for [[Catholic emancipation|Catholic Emancipation]] as advocated by [[Daniel O'Connell]].  Hackett was sued for libel on multiple occasions for his [[Caricature|caricatures]] of political rivals.  Printed on O'Connell Street bi-weekly, it circulated counties Tipperary, Waterford, Kilkenny, Cork and Limerick.  In its later years it assumed a Catholic-Whig political leaning.  Printing ceased when it was acquired by the ''Tipperary Independent'' (1882-1906) in 1883.\n\n== Culture ==\n\n=== Museums and Galleries ===\n[[File:Cluain Meala (Clonmel), The Main Guard - geograph.org.uk - 260570.jpg|thumb|[[Main Guard (Clonmel)|The Main Guard]]]]\nTipperary County Museum tells the history of [[County Tipperary]] from the [[Stone Age]] to the present. It is also host to many special exhibitions each year. It is the first custom built county museum in Ireland.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.southtippheritage.ie/en/Heritage%20Centres/|title=South Tipperary Co Museum|publisher=South Tipperary Heritage \u2013 S.Tipp. County Council|accessdate=28 June 2009}}{{dead link|date=November 2010}}</ref>\n\nThe [[Main Guard (Clonmel)|Main Guard]] was a civic building until 1810 when it was converted to shops. During recent restoration, some of its sandstone columns were found to have been 'reclaimed' from the now demolished abbey of [[Inislounaght Abbey|Inislounaght]] at [[Marlfield, Clonmel|Marlfield]]. It has been used in the past as a [[Tholsel]] or office to collect tolls, duties and customs dues, a place for civic gatherings and as a court. It now houses an exhibition showing the historic development of Clonmel, including a model of the town as it appeared in the 13th century.\n\nThe South Tipperary Arts Centre opened in 1996. The Arts Centre hosts around 12 exhibitions per year and a variety of art classes for adults and children. As well as presenting a range of visual arts exhibitions in the main gallery space, the centre also host events such as music, performance, poetry readings and dance. The centre has a spacious upstairs studio which is used for short term exhibitions & screenings, as well as for a variety of classes and workshops. It is also a rehearsal space for theatre, dance, music, and is available for meetings and seminars.\n\n=== Theatre and cinema ===\nThe White Memorial Theatre building is a former Weslyan/[[Methodist]] Chapel and was designed and built by local architect [[William Tinsley (architect)|William Tinsley]] in 1843.<ref name=\"Shee & Watson\">{{cite book|last=Shee|first=Elizabeth|title=Clonmel: An Architectural Guide|year=1975|publisher=An Taisce|isbn=978-0-903693-02-8|pages=39|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=mQyspwAACAAJ&dq=clonmel+an+architectural+guide+shee&hl=en&sa=X&ei=8eoxT-GCOoKDhQfFncCOBQ&ved=0CDEQ6AEwAA|author2=Sydney John Watson|accessdate=8 February 2012}}</ref> The building was purchased in 1975 by St. Mary's Choral Society,<ref>[http://www.stmaryschoralsociety.com/homepage.html stmaryschoralsociety.com<!-- Bot generated title -->] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090330063311/http://www.stmaryschoralsociety.com/homepage.html |date=30 March 2009 }}</ref> who put on an average of 2 shows a year in the building. The building also host shows by the Stage Craft Youth Theatre group and special event during the year.\n\nClonmel has a vibrant youth arts sector. Stagecraft Youth Theatre was founded in 1998 by current Artistic Director Shane Dempsey. Stagecraft provides training for young actors in all aspects of theatre practise. Stagecraft is renowned for producing vibrant work in a fun child centred environment. Stagecraft is one of Ireland's largest youth theatre's and is affiliated to NAYD. They have recently staged works by Alex Jones, Enda Walsh, Hannah Burke, Jack Thorne and Moira Buffini.\n\nIn 2011 Shane Dempsey founded The Hub, a 45-seat studio theatre in Albert Street. The Hub is home to Stagecraft.\n\nThe [[Ward Anderson|IMC]], with five screens and located on Kickham Street, is the town's only remaining cinema.<ref>[http://www.omniplex.ie/cinema/cinema/clonmel Clonmel | Omniplex Cinemas, Ireland \u2013 Book Movie Tickets Now<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref> Several other cinemas formerly operated in the town including the Ritz, which opened in 1940<ref>{{cite web|url=http://two.archiseek.com/2009/1939-ritz-cinema-athlone-co-westmeath/|title=1939 \u2013 Ritz Cinema, Athlone, Co. Westmeath|year=2010|publisher=Archiseek|accessdate=8 July 2010}}</ref> and was located on the site of the present [[Irish League of Credit Unions|Credit Union]]. The first cinema in the town opened in January 1913 as the Clonmel Cinema Theatre, soon to be renamed the Clonmel Electric Picture Palace. It was located at the rear of No. 35 Gladstone Street. It was soon followed by John Magner's Theatre at the Mall, which burned to the ground in 1919, to be re-built in 1921 with an increased capacity of over a thousand seats. It was eventually named the Regal Theatre and remodelled as an 850-seat theatre, which finally closed in 2001.<ref>[http://cinematreasures.org/theater/852/ cinematreasures.org]</ref> It was in the Regal Theatre where the tenor [[Frank Patterson]] made his stage debut.<ref>[http://www.rte.ie/ten/2001/0219/clonmel.html rte.ie] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20121102095105/http://www.rte.ie/ten/2001/0219/clonmel.html |date=2 November 2012 }}</ref> The Oisin, in O'Connell Street, was of a similar scale and was also built in 1921. It was on the site of the present day [[Heatons]] but burned to the ground in 1965. The last film to be shown there was ''[[A Patch of Blue]]''.<ref>{{cite book\n|last=O'Donnell\n|first=Sean\n|title=Clonmel 1900\u20131932: A History\n|url=https://books.google.com/?id=00CFPgAACAAJ&dq=clonmel+1900-1932\n|accessdate=8 July 2010\n|year=2009\n|publisher=BPR Publishers\n|isbn=978-0-9562139-0-7\n|pages=139 to 146}}</ref>\n\n=== Festivals ===\n[[File:Community Park.jpg|thumb|alt=Street Performance|Street Performance at Clonmel Junction Festival 2004]]\n[[File:Parnell St Clonmel Busking.JPG|thumb|Mitchell Street, during the Busking Festival in 2014]]\nFor nine days from the first week-end of July, the town hosts the annual [[Clonmel Junction Festival]]. It consists of a mix of [[street theatre]], rock, [[Music of Ireland#Traditional|traditional]] and [[world music]]. Several international acts visit the festival each year. In the last few years, young local bands have also had an opportunity to showcase their talents. Children from local schools and [[Community organization|community groups]] are encouraged to participate with support from local artists.\n\nClonmel is home to the International Film Festival Ireland, which focuses on independent films. Its inaugural event was during September 2009<ref>[https://archive.is/20120903165147/http://www.nationalist.ie/the/Clonmel-to-host-international-film.5419884.jp Clonmel to host international film festival| The Nationalist, 4 July 2009 ]</ref> and ran for five days. It has become an annual event, occurring every September.<ref>{{cite web| title=International Film Festival Ireland \u2013 Official Website| work=southtippfilm.com| url=http://www.southtippfilm.com/| accessdate=5 April 2012| archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120314234537/http://www.southtippfilm.com/| archive-date=14 March 2012| url-status=dead| df=dmy-all}}</ref> The 2010 event expanded to include a Youth Film Festival, that showcased locally made short films.<ref>[https://archive.is/20120904233650/http://www.nationalist.ie/clonmel/Film-festival-visitors-34blown-away34.6543599.jp Film festival visitors \"blown away\" by warm welcome| ''The Nationalist'', 4 July 2009 ]</ref>\n\nThe Clonmel Busking festival runs for four days every August. It provides free music events during the day in Clonmel town centre, while at night a number a concerts take place in various venues throughout the town.<ref>[http://www.clonmelbuskingfestival.com/#!about-us/c1se Clonmel Busking Festival] \u2013 official website</ref>\n\n=== Music ===\n[[Banna Chluain Meala]] (literally translating as 'Clonmel band') was founded in 1971. Originally a brass band, Banna Chluain Meala later developed as a brass and reed band, which included concert, marching and fieldshow performances.  The band also has a colour guard section which enhances marching and fieldshow performances. The total complement of the band has ranged from 100 to 150 members throughout the years.  The band has travelled widely abroad to the United Kingdom, the Netherlands, France, Italy and Chicago in the United States of America and represented Ireland at an International Festival in Cheb in the Czech Republic in 2004 to celebrate the new entrants to the European Union.  Banna Chluain Meala is one of Ireland's most honoured bands.  They hold concert band championship titles on national and international levels.  As a marching band they have had unparalleled success nationally, being crowned IMBA Irish champions in the highest division on twelve occasions (1991, 1995, 1996, 1997, 1998, 1999, 2006, 2007, 2009, 2010, 2011, 2015).  They have also had success abroad, most notably as Open Class champions at the British Youth Band Championships at Wembley in 1994.\n\nClonmel has hosted the Irish traditional music festival, the [[Fleadh Cheoil]], on five occasions from 1992\u201394 inclusive, and again in 2003 and 2004.\n\nOne of the better-known songs concerning Clonmel is \"The Gaol of Cluain Meala,\" a translation from the turn of the 19th century by a Cork man, [[Jeremiah Joseph Callanan]], of the traditional [[Irish language|Irish-language]] song \"Pr\u00edos\u00fan Chluain Meala\".<ref>Lyrics and info. on [http://www.searcs-web.com/anon2.html ''The Gaol of Cl\u00faain Meala''] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120215143540/http://www.searcs-web.com/anon2.html |date=15 February 2012 }}.  The original can be found at: http://songsinirish.com/priosun-chluain-meala-lyrics/ \"Pr\u00edos\u00fan Chluain Meala\".</ref> It was revived by the celebrated balladeer [[Luke Kelly]] in the 1960s. The narrator in the Irish republican song \"[[Galtee Mountain Boy]]\" farewells Clonmel in the song. The song was written by Patsy Halloran from Clonmel.<ref>http://www.songdocs.com/GalteeMountainBoy.doc</ref>\n\nMusic venues in Clonmel include The Piper Inn, famous for hosting a show by Irish rock legends [[Thin Lizzy]].\n\n===Clonmel in literature===\n''Vertue rewarded, or The Irish princess'' (1693), one of the earliest [[romance novel]]s written in the English language, tells the story of \"Merinda\" from High Street, Clonmel and a [[Williamite]] officer stationed in the town during the [[Jacobite War in Ireland|Jacobite war]].<ref>{{cite journal|last=McDermott |first=Hubert |title=      * Vertue Rewarded: The First Anglo-Irish Novel|journal=Studies: An Irish Quarterly Review|publisher= Irish Province of the Society of Jesus |volume= 75|issue=  298 (Summer 1986)|pages=  177\u2013185 (9 pages)|year=1986|jstor=30090731}}</ref>\n\n[[Raymond Chandler]]'s 1939 novel ''[[The Big Sleep]]'' features Rusty Regan as a main character: \"A big curly-headed Irishman from Clonmel, with sad eyes and a smile as wide as Wilshire Boulevard.\"<ref>{{cite book|last=Chandler|first=Raymond|title=The Big Sleep|publisher=Penguin|edition=1992|pages=10|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=fLgrAQAAIAAJ&dq=%22the+big+sleep%22&q=clonmel#search_anchor|accessdate=30 June 2011|year=1992}}</ref>\n\n[[Charles Kickham]]'s 1873 novel ''Knocknagow'' had two main characters modeled off Clonmel locals.  These were his cousins, Dr T.J Crean Sr  as ''\"Arthur O'Conner\"'' and his wife Clara Crean (nee Kickham) as ''\"Mary Kearney\",'' who both lived on Queen Street at the time.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://humphrysfamilytree.com/Kickham/dr.thomas.crean.html|title=Crean, Dr. Thomas Crean|last=Mark|first=Humphrys|date=|website=Humphrys Family Tree|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=April 8, 2020}}</ref>\n\n== Sport ==\n{{More citations needed section|date=March 2010}}\n\n=== Association Football ===\nClonmel is home to Clonmel Celtic, Old Bridge, Wilderness Rovers, Redmondstown and Clonmel Town who play in the TSDL League.\n\n===Athletics===\nClonmel is home to Clonmel Athletic Club.\n\n=== Rugby ===\nClonmel Rugby Club plays in the All Ireland League, Division 2C. The rugby club was founded in 1892. In 1990 the club opened their new club House coinciding with the first ever [[Soviet Union national rugby union team|Soviet Union rugby team]] visit to Ireland. In their centenary year, 1992, they hosted [[London Irish|London Irish RFC]] against [[Shannon RFC]] in a memorable game played at the club grounds. Clonmel won the Munster Junior Cup for the first time in its 122-year history in 2014 and followed that up with a Munster Junior League (Division 1) title and the Munster Junior Challenge Cup in the 2015 season.\n\n=== Cricket ===\nClonmel's cricket club plays teams in the Munster Cricket Union Senior 2 and Senior 3 leagues. The cricket club currently fields 1 adult teams and 2 youth teams. All play their home games in the Presentation Convent Field. Clonmel's cricket Club was originally started by a group of friends who originally played the game socially, however the club has been playing competitive cricket for the last 20 years.\n\n=== Horse Racing and Coursing ===\nClonmel is noted in [[greyhound]] circles for being the home of the annual National [[Hare Coursing]] meeting in early February at [[Clonmel Racecourse]] located in the Powerstown area of the town. Also Included in this event is the Ladies' International Open Meeting and the coursing derby. At this time each year, Clonmel's population is swollen by a large influx of sports people from Ireland, the UK, and from as far afield as Australia, New Zealand, the United States and the Middle East.\n\n=== Rowing and boat building ===\nClonmel has two clubs associated with recreational activity on the river Suir, both of which are based in Irishtown.\n\n====Clonmel Rowing Club (CRC)====\nClonmel Rowing Club (CRC), was founded in 1869 and is one of the oldest sporting clubs in the town. It is located on Moor's Island, on the [[Suir]], about 500 meters west of the town centre. The club colours are Royal Blue and White. Sporting success in the early 1900s culminated in the winning of the Senior Men's 'eight' championships in 1920. The club is affectionately known locally as \"The Island\". In winter, training takes place on a 4-mile stretch of the river to the west of the town, from the clubhouse to [[Knocklofty, Clonmel|Knocklofty]] bridge. In the summer months this stretch is reduced to 2 miles as far as Sandybanks, near [[Marlfield, Clonmel|Marlfield]] village.\n\nFlooding has become a perennial problem, especially noticeable in recent years. The flow becomes so fast that rowing in January is not possible on this part of the Suir. Within a 25-mile radius there are two locations where the club can still train satisfactorily, [[Cappoquin]] and [[Fiddown]].\n\nCRC has a newly constructed, purpose built boat house since 1979, with boat storage on the ground floor. Upstairs are two [[Squash (sport)|squash]] courts, a function hall and dressing rooms. Currently one squash court is being used as the gym.\n\nIn the new millennium, the club's veterans are still competing strongly. Women's rowing in Clonmel has developed culminating in Junior Women's 'double [[scull]]' and Junior women's 'eight' championship wins in 2003 and 2005.\n\n==== Workmen's Boat Club ====\nThe Workmen's Boat Club was established in 1883. The property was leased from the Bagwell estate until 1999, when it was finally purchased by the club. One of the major undertakings of the club in recent years has been the restoration of the historic racing craft ''Cruiskeen'', which was built in the 1840s by GAA founder member [[Maurice Davin]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.rte.ie/radio1/seascapes/1173971.html |title=Seascapes News Summary \u2013 26th November 2007 |publisher=RT\u00c9 |accessdate=4 September 2009 |date=27 November 2007 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080503075025/http://www.rte.ie/radio1/seascapes/1173971.html |archivedate=3 May 2008 }}</ref> The project, outsourced to 'Conservation | Letterfrack', took several years of meticulous cleaning, treatment and repair and the 38&nbsp;ft./11.6m timber boat is now on permanent display in the County Museum, Clonmel.<ref>{{cite book|last=Marine Committee of the Heritage Council|author2=Sven Habermann|title=The Future of Maritime and Inland Waterways Collections|editor=Eleanor Flegg|publisher=The Heritage Council|year=2007|isbn=1-901137-99-6|url=http://www.heritagecouncil.ie/fileadmin/user_upload/Publications/Marine/Maritime_Collect_Proceedings.pdf|display-authors=etal|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110927173626/http://www.heritagecouncil.ie/fileadmin/user_upload/Publications/Marine/Maritime_Collect_Proceedings.pdf|archivedate=27 September 2011|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\n=== GAA Clubs ===\nClonmel is home to several [[Gaelic Athletic Association]] (GAA) clubs. [[Clonmel \u00d3g GAA|Clonmel \u00d3g]] the most recently established GAA club in the town was set up in 1984 and it competes in the senior division only 31 years after being formed.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.clonmelog.ie/|title=Clonmel Og|year=2009|publisher=Clonmel Og|accessdate=16 March 2010|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090821110441/http://www.clonmelog.ie/|archivedate=21 August 2009|df=dmy-all}}</ref> [[Moyle Rovers GAA]] club is just outside the town and has been a dominant force in recent decades.\n\n[[Clonmel Commercials]], the 2016 Munster Football Club champions, are based in the town, on the Western Road. They reached the semi-finals of the 2015-16 All Ireland Football Club championships, losing out to Ballyboden St. Endas, who would go on to win the championship. Sister club, [[St. Mary's Hurling Club]], are also located on Western Road.\n\n==Education==\n\n===Primary schools===\n[[File:St. Mary's Parochial School (Model School), Clonmel.jpg|thumb|right|St. Mary's Parochial School]]\n* [[Gaelscoil Chluain Meala]] has around 200<ref>[http://www.education.ie/panels/foundepl.jsp?page=3&educator2=Primary+Schools&pcategory=10917&language=EN&county=Tipperary+S.R.&educator=Primary+Schools&ecategory=12016&roll_no=&Submit=Submit Primary Schools] education.ie</ref> students. Located at Irishtown and originally the Free School, the building was designed by two pupils of the renowned architect [[John Nash (architect)|John Nash]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.buildingsofireland.ie/niah/search.jsp?type=record&county=TS&regno=22116030|title=National Inventory of Architectural Heritage \u2013 Tipperary South|year=2010|publisher=Department of the Environment, Heritage and Local Government.|accessdate=3 June 2010}}</ref> It was for a number of years the offices of South Tipperary County Council.\n* [[St Mary's Parochial School, Clonmel]], also known as the Model School, traces its roots to the Incorporated Society School of 1832. It is located on the Western Road. (''[[Church of Ireland]]'')\n*St Oliver's [[National school (Ireland)|national school]] was founded in 1982.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.education.ie/insreports/report1_19645E.htm|title=Whole School Evaluation REPORT St. Oliver Plunkett's NS Clonmel, County Tipperary Uimhir rolla:  19645E|date=October 2009|publisher=Department of Education and Science|accessdate=15 January 2011}}</ref> It is situated at Heywood Road.\n* St.Mary's CBS is located in Irishtown directly beside the Gaelscoil.\n* St.Peter and Paul's CBS.\n* Sisters of Charity Girls School.\n* Presentation Primary School.\n\n===Secondary schools===\n* [[Presentation Secondary School, Clonmel|Presentation Convent]], for girls, (Roman Catholic)\n* Loreto Convent, for girls, (Roman Catholic)\n* [[CBS High School Clonmel|CBS High School]], for boys, (Roman Catholic)\n* [[Gaelchol\u00e1iste Ch\u00e9itinn]], co-educational. Part of the [[Clonmel Central Technical Institute]]. Established in 2004,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.cti-clonmel.ie/miscellaneous/newsletters/edition03.pdf |title='Name Change Goes Ahead' |publisher=VEC |page=1 |date=2 June 2004 |accessdate=23 May 2011 }}{{dead link|date=June 2017 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.cti-clonmel.ie/miscellaneous/newsletters/welcomeletter.pdf |title=Gaelchol\u00e1iste Ch\u00e9itinn |publisher=VEC |page=1 |date=25 June 2004 |accessdate=23 May 2011 }}{{dead link|date=June 2017 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref> the school teaches through the medium of Irish. It was established as an autonomous school within the [[Vocational Education Committee]] system in response to a demand for second level education through the medium of Irish.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.tipperarystar.ie/3582/Gael-Choliste-Chitinn--fostering.1399863.jp |archive-url=https://archive.is/20120914122238/http://www.tipperarystar.ie/3582/Gael-Choliste-Chitinn--fostering.1399863.jp |url-status=dead |archive-date=14 September 2012 |title=Gael Chol\u00e1iste Ch\u00e9itinn \u2013 fostering the Irish language of a distinctive nation |date=24 March 2006 |publisher=Tipperary Star |accessdate=3 June 2010 }}</ref>\n* [[Col\u00e1iste Chluain Meala]], co-educational. Formerly known as ''The [[Clonmel Central Technical Institute]] Secondary School''<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.cti-clonmel.ie/miscellaneous/newsletters/edition02.pdf |title=The Central Technical Institute Newsletter |date=29 March 2004 |publisher=VEC |page=1 |accessdate=3 June 2010 }}{{dead link|date=June 2017 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref> which traces its history back to 1842.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.cti-clonmel.ie/centraltechnicalinstitute/history.shtml |title=The Central Technical Institute Website |publisher=VEC |accessdate=23 May 2011 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090621220620/http://www.cti-clonmel.ie/centraltechnicalinstitute/history.shtml |archivedate=21 June 2009 }}</ref> Under the control of the local [[Education and Training Board]].\n* CTI [[Senior College]], co-educational. Part of the [[Clonmel Central Technical Institute]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.cti-clonmel.ie/|title=The Central Technical Institute Website|publisher=VEC|accessdate=23 May 2011}}</ref> and under the control of the local [[Education and Training Board]]. There is an official website listing PLC courses.\n\n===Third level===\nClonmel is home to one [[List of higher education institutions in the Republic of Ireland|third-level college]], [[Limerick Institute of Technology|LIT]]. The Clonmel Campus of LIT offers courses in Business, Creative Multimedia, Digital Animation Production and Marketing with Languages. The Creative Multimedia & Digital Animation Production degrees are operated under the LIT Limerick School of Art and Design. The LIT Clonmel campus is located along the Clonmel Inner Relief Road, but it is proposed that it will move to a new location within the town centre in the future.\n\n===Training===\nClonmel Youth Training Entreprises Limited was established in 1984 by voluntary and business people, who saw the need to tackle the growing issue of unemployment and the related consequences of early school leavers in Clonmel.\n\nToday the primary objective of helping young people to become mature, confident and competent young adults, ready for the world of work, still holds true.\n\n==Transport==\n\n===Roads===\nClonmel is located on the [[N24 road (Ireland)|N24]], the national primary roadway that links the cities of Limerick and Waterford. The N24 westbound connects Clonmel to junction 10 of the [[Cork (city)|Cork]] to [[Dublin]] [[M8 motorway (Ireland)|M8 motorway]], while eastbound it links the town with [[Kilkenny]] via the [[N76 road (Ireland)|N76]].  \n\n[[Charles Bianconi]], onetime mayor of the town, ran his pioneering public transport system of horse-drawn carriages from Clonmel.\n\n===Rail===\n[[Clonmel railway station]] opened on 1 May 1852.<ref>{{cite web | title=Clonmel station | work=Railscot \u2013 Irish Railways | url=http://www.railscot.co.uk/Ireland/Irish_railways.pdf |format=PDF| accessdate=7 September 2007}}</ref> Today there are two trains daily to [[Waterford]] via [[Carrick on Suir]], and two to [[Limerick Junction]] via [[Cahir]] and [[County Tipperary|Tipperary]] which has main-line connections to [[Dublin]]. There is no Sunday service.\n\n===Waterways===\nThe River Suir had been made navigable to Clonmel from 1760 when completion of the [[River Suir Navigation]] in the 19th century allowed large vessels to reach the town's [[quay]]s.\n\n==People associated with Clonmel==\n* [[Anne Anderson (diplomat)|Anne Anderson]] (born 1952), was Ireland\u2019s  first female Ambassador to the United States of America, United Nations, France, Monaco and European Union, born in Clonmel.\n* [[Bonaventura Baron]] (1610\u20131696), a distinguished Franciscan humanist, philosopher and writer was born in Clonmel.\n* [[Charles Bianconi]] (1786\u20131875), one-time mayor of Clonmel, ran his pioneering public transport system of horse-drawn carriages from Clonmel\n* [[George Borrow]] (1803\u20131881), [[Multilingualism|polyglot]], [[ethnologist]] of the [[Romani people]] and author of ''[[Lavengro]]'', in which he briefly writes of his time in Clonmel, lived here in 1815\n* [[Francis Bryan]] (1490\u20131550), English courtier and diplomat during the reign of [[Henry VIII of England|Henry VIII]], died in Clonmel in 1550<ref>[https://books.google.com/books?id=f3oPx3711Z0C&pg=PA47&dq=%22governor+general%22+ireland++francis+bryan&cd=1#v=onepage&q=%22governor%20general%22%20ireland%20%20francis%20bryan&f=false ''The Spear and the Spindle''] p48</ref>\n* [[Austin Carroll]] (1835\u20131909), Irish Catholic nun and writer\n* [[Thomas Chamney]], Irish athlete who ran 800m in Beijing Olympics in 2008\n* [[William J. Duane]] (1780\u20131865), American politician and lawyer from [[Pennsylvania]], was born in Clonmel.\n* [[Dave Foley (rugby union)|Dave Foley]] is a professional rugby union player\n* [[Sarah Pim Grubb]] (1746\u20131832), Quaker businesswoman, wife of John Grubb, died in Clonmel\n* [[Vincent Hanley]] (1954\u20131987), a pioneering Irish radio DJ and television presenter, nicknamed \"Fab Vinny\". He worked mainly for [[Raidi\u00f3 Teilif\u00eds \u00c9ireann]] and was the first Irish celebrity to die from an AIDS-related illness<ref>[http://www.rte.ie/tv/theafternoonshow/2008/1211/giftguide.html Vincent Hanley, AIDs related death \u2013 charity appeal]</ref>\n* [[Sir Lionel Milman, 7th Baronet]] (1877\u20131962), Anglo-Irish first-class cricketer and British Army officer\n* [[Fred Murray]], former professional football player, now personal masseuse for Foo Fighters member Dave Grohl\n* [[Vivian Murray]], businessman\n* [[Pat O'Callaghan]] was an Irish athlete and [[Athletics at the 1928 Summer Olympics \u2013 Men's hammer throw|1928 Olympic gold medalist]]\n* [[M\u00edche\u00e1l \u00d3 S\u00failleabh\u00e1in]] (1950\u20132018), an Irish musician, held Professorship of Music at the Irish World Music Centre of the University of Limerick\n* [[Frank Patterson]] (1938\u20132000), one of Ireland's most famous [[tenors]], was native to the town\n* [[Ramsay Weston Phipps]] (1838\u20131923), military historian, born in Clonmel, lived there off and on throughout his life\n* [[Rozanna Purcell]], model and Miss Universe Ireland 2010\n* [[Adi Roche]], co-founder of [[Chernobyl Children's Project International]] and [[1997 Irish presidential election|1997]] candidate for the [[President of Ireland|Irish Presidency]]\n* [[Andrea Roche]], best known Irish model and Miss Ireland 1997\n* [[Symon Semeonis]], or Simon Fitzsimons, was a 14th-century Franciscan friar who left Clonmel in 1323 on pilgrimage to the [[Holy Land]]. The account of his \"Itinerary\" is preserved in a manuscript in the Library of Corpus Christi College, Cambridge\n* [[Laurence Sterne]] (1713\u201368), author of ''[[The Life and Opinions of Tristram Shandy, Gentleman]]'', was born in the town, though his family returned to England soon after\n* [[Anthony Trollope]] (1815\u20131852), a noted author, worked in the town for a period\n* [[Stephen White (Jesuit)|Stephen White]] (1575\u20131646) was an Irish Jesuit, historian and antiquarian born in Clonmel, who wrote about the early Irish saints\n\n{{Historical populations\n| state = collapsed\n|1821|15590\n|1831|15134\n|1841|13505\n|1851|11589\n|1861|11646\n|1871|10112\n|1881|9325\n|1891|8480\n|1901|10167\n|1911|10209\n|1926|9056\n|1936|9391\n|1946|9857\n|1951|10471\n|1956|11134\n|1961|11087\n|1966|11457\n|1971|12291\n|1981|14808\n|1986|15517\n|1991|15562\n|1996|16182\n|2002|16910\n|2006|17008\n|2011|17908\n|2016|17140\n| footnote=<ref>Sources: [http://www.cso.ie/census CSO] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20050309005718/http://www.cso.ie/census/ |date=9 March 2005 }} and [http://www.histpop.org/ohpr/servlet/ HistPop]. Allowance has not been made for periodic changes to borough boundaries.\n</ref>\n}}\n\n==Sister towns==\nClonmel is [[town twinning|twinned]] with several places:\n\n<!-- NOTE ON FLAG ICONS : Please do not add flag icons to this section. There is a longstanding convention to avoid flag icons (per MOS:FLAG and WP:CON) because it causes too many edit wars over whether national or regional flags should be used. -->\n{|\n|-\n| valign=\"top\" |\n* [[Costa Masnaga]], Lombardy, Italy.\n* [[Gangi, Sicily]], Italy.\n* [[Reading, Berkshire|Reading]], England.<ref name=\"Reading twinning\">{{cite web|url=http://www.reading.gov.uk/council/town-twinning/ |title=Reading \u2013 Town Twinning |accessdate=14 July 2013 |work=Reading Borough Council |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130509063652/http://www.reading.gov.uk/council/town-twinning/ |archivedate=9 May 2013 |df=dmy }}</ref>\n| valign=\"top\" |\n* [[Eysines]], [[Aquitaine]], France.\n* [[Trofaiach]], [[Styria]], Austria.\n* [[Peoria, Illinois]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://dublin.usembassy.gov/sister_cities.html |title=sister cities |last=U.S. Embassy Dublin |publisher=U.S. Department of State |accessdate=6 August 2009 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090802225732/http://dublin.usembassy.gov/sister_cities.html |archivedate=2 August 2009 |df=dmy }}</ref>\n* [[Roeselare]], Belgium\n|}\n\n==See also==\n* [[Clonmel Borstal]]\n* [[Ferryhouse|St Joseph's Industrial School, Ferryhouse]]\n* [[Grange, County Tipperary]]\n* [[List of towns and villages in the Republic of Ireland|List of towns and villages in Ireland]]\n* [[Market Houses in the Republic of Ireland|Market Houses in Ireland]]\n* [[Siege of Clonmel]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|colwidth=30em}}\n* [https://archive.org/details/historyclonmel00burkgoog ''History of Clonmel''] William P. Burke 1907 from [[Internet Archive]].\n* [https://archive.org/details/anglerinireland00biltgoog/page/n31 <!-- pg=14 quote=clonmel. --> Observations on fishing and other 'native fauna', Clonmel, 1833]\n* [https://books.google.com/books?id=wiZIAAAAMAAJ&pg=PR1&lpg=PR1&dq=inglis+ireland+writer&source=web&ots=x0yBuswmya&sig=jwna3PQtxxFGY0-TiwFhrnmSqWQ&hl=en&sa=X&oi=book_result&resnum=9&ct=result#PPA130,M1 From Cahir to Clonmel, 1834]\n* White, James : ''My Clonmel Scrapbook'' : 1995 based on 1907 original {{ISBN|978-1-899003-16-7}}\n* ''The Cistercian Abbeys of Tipperary'' (inc. Inislaunaght founded 1147-8) [https://web.archive.org/web/20120214131357/http://www.fourcourtspress.ie/product.php?intProductID=183 from Four Courts Press] {{ISBN|978-1-85182-380-2}}\n* Watson, Sydney John : ''A Dinner of Herbs: A History of Old Saint Mary's Church, Clonmel'' 1988 {{ISBN|978-0-9513212-0-1}}\n* McGrath,  Br\u00edd (ed.): ''The Minute Book of the Corporation of Clonmel, 1608\u20131649'' : [http://www.irmss.ie/ Irish Manuscripts Commission]  : 2006 :  {{ISBN|978-1-874280-53-8}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category}}\n\n{{County Tipperary}}\n\n[[Category:Clonmel| ]]\n[[Category:County towns in the Republic of Ireland]]\n[[Category:Towns and villages in County Tipperary]]\n[[Category:Boroughs in the Republic of Ireland]]\n[[Category:Iffa and Offa East]]\n", "name_user": "Certes", "label": "safe", "comment": "Fix links to retailers, replaced:Argos\u2192Argos,typo(s) fixed: second level \u2192 second-level, (nee \u2192 (n\u00e9e, \u2019s \u2192 's", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Clonmel"}
{"title_page": "The Citadel Bulldogs football", "text_new": "{{Infobox NCAA football school\n| TeamName         = The Citadel Bulldogs\n| CurrentSeason    = 2019 The Citadel Bulldogs football team\n| FirstYear        = {{start date|1905}}\n| Image            = The Citadel Athletics script.svg\n| ImageSize        = 125\n| AthleticDirector = [[Mike Capaccio]]\n| HeadCoach = [[Brent Thompson (American football)|Brent Thompson]]\n| HeadCoachYear    = 4th\n| HCWins           = 25 <!-- Through 2018 season -->\n| HCLosses         = 18 <!-- Through 2018 season -->\n| Stadium          = [[Johnson Hagood Stadium]]\n| FieldName        = Sansom Field\n| StadiumBuilt     = 1948\n| StadCapacity     = 21,000\n| StadSurface      = Natural Grass\n| Location         = [[Charleston, South Carolina]]\n| Conference = [[Southern Conference]]\n| ConfDivision     = \n| PastAffiliations = \n| ATWins           = 508\n| ATLosses         = 559\n| ATTies           = 32\n| BowlWins         = 1\n| BowlLosses       = 0\n| BowlTies         = \n| PlayoffApps      = 5\n| Playoffs         = 2\u20135\n| NatlTitles       = \n| ConfTitles       = 4 (1961, 1992, 2015, 2016)\n| DivTitles        = \n| Heismans         = \n| AllAmericans     = \n| uniform          =\n| FightSong        = \"The Fighting Light Brigade\"\n| MascotDisplay    = Bulldog\n| MarchingBand     = [[The Regimental Band and Pipes]]\n| WebsiteName      = citadelsports.com\n| WebsiteURL       = http://www.citadelsports.com\n}}\n'''The Citadel Bulldogs football''' program represents [[The Citadel, The Military College of South Carolina]] in the [[NCAA Division I FCS|NCAA Division I Football Championship Subdivision (FCS)]]. The Bulldogs play in the [[Southern Conference]], as they have since 1936.  The Bulldogs are coached by [[Brent Thompson (American football)|Brent Thompson]], who was hired on January 19, 2016 to replace [[Mike Houston (American football)|Mike Houston]], who became the head football coach of [[James Madison Dukes football|James Madison University]] on January 18, 2016.<ref>{{cite news|author=Jeff Hartsell|title=The Citadel introduces new football coach Mike Houston |url=http://www.postandcourier.com/article/20140109/PC20/140109440/1032/citadel-introduces-houston-as-new-coach|accessdate=January 9, 2014|newspaper=[[Post and Courier]] |location=Charleston, SC|date=January 9, 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.live5news.com/story/30994395/mike-houston-leaves-the-citadel-for-james-madison|title=Mike Houston leaves The Citadel for James Madison|author=Kevin Bilodeau|date=January 18, 2016|accessdate=January 18, 2016|publisher=[[WCSC-TV]]}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.live5news.com/story/31005256/report-the-citadel-to-name-brent-thompson-as-new-head-coach|publisher=WCSC-TV|title=The Citadel names Brent Thompson as new head coach |author=Kevin Bilodeau|date=January 19, 2016|accessdate=January 19, 2016}}</ref>\n\n==History==\n{{See also|List of The Citadel Bulldogs football seasons}}\n\n==Facilities==\nThe Bulldogs first recorded stadium was College Park, located in the northeast corner of [[Hampton Park (Charleston, SC)|Hampton Park]] in [[Charleston, South Carolina]]. This field predated the current [[College Park (Charleston)|College Park]] at the same site, which is used as a practice facility for [[The Citadel Bulldogs baseball]]. Due to increasing attendance and the poor state of the stadium, the Bulldogs moved to the original [[Johnson Hagood Stadium (1927)|Johnson Hagood Stadium]] in 1927. In 1948, that stadium was replaced by the current [[Johnson Hagood Stadium]], which lies just to the south of The Citadel's gates in Charleston. \n\n[[File:CitadelStadium.jpg|thumb|right|Johnson Hagood Stadium]]\nJohnson Hagood is a 21,000 seat stadium, in which The Citadel routinely ranks in the top 25 in attendance at the FCS level.  In 2001, the Altman Athletic Center opened in the south end zone, complete with new home and visitor's locker rooms, official's locker rooms, and an upstairs hospitality area for donors.  In 2008, The Citadel completed a re-construction of the west stands and West Side Tower.  The stands contain reserved premium seats and bleacher seats, while the tower, shared with the South Carolina National Guard, contains twelve suites, a club level, and state of the art press box.  During preparation for construction, workers discovered the remains of sailors from failed test runs of the ''[[H.L. Hunley (submarine)|H.L. Hunley]]''.  These remains were reinterred in Magnolia Cemetery in Charleston.\n\nBeginning in 2012, The Citadel implemented a points system for parking and seat selection in Johnson Hagood Stadium, joining many large programs who use similar systems. The program is designed to reward long-time and large donors to The Citadel athletics by giving them preference in selecting seat and parking locations.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://foundation.citadel.edu/Document.Doc?id=401|title=Priority Points System|publisher=The Citadel|accessdate=2012-05-12}}</ref>\n\nIn 2016, The Citadel determined that lead paint needed remediation on the east (visitor's) side of the stadium.  The work resulted in the entire east side being closed for the first game of the [[2016 The Citadel Bulldogs football team|2016 season]] and some sections being opened for subsequent games.  The capacity was thus 10,500 for the first game and about 15,000 for later games.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.postandcourier.com/20160829/160829380/citadel-considers-tearing-down-visitors-side-at-johnson-hagood-stadium|newspaper=Post and Courier|author=Jeff Hartsell|location=Charleston, SC|date=August 29, 2016|title=Citadel considers tearing down visitors\u2019 side at Johnson Hagood Stadium|accessdate=October 12, 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.postandcourier.com/20160909/160909467/citadel-football-returns-to-half-of-johnson-hagood-stadium|newspaper=Post and Courier|author=Jeff Hartsell|location=Charleston, SC|date=September 9, 2016|title=Citadel football returns to (half of) Johnson Hagood Stadium|accessdate=October 12, 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.postandcourier.com/20161011/161019898/citadel-home-at-last-with-nations-best-4-road-wins|newspaper=Post and Courier|author=Jeff Hartsell|location=Charleston, SC|date=October 11, 2016|title=Citadel home at last, with nation\u2019s best 4 road wins|accessdate=October 12, 2016}}</ref>  The Board of Visitors decided to fully renovate the east side of the stadium, announcing that decision on December 2, 2016.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.postandcourier.com/sports/citadel-notes-stadium-s-east-side-to-be-renovated-georgia/article_9ccf5690-b8ca-11e6-b48e-6b78a3d257d5.html|newspaper=Post and Courier|author=Jeff Hartsell|location=Charleston, SC|date=October 11, 2016|title=Citadel Notes: Stadium's east side to be renovated; Georgia Tech on 2019 schedule}}</ref>\n\n===Practice and on-campus facilities===\nPractices are held at the Maybank Triplets Practice Facility, an artificial turf field at the north edge of campus.  The Bulldogs utilize Seignious Hall, located across from [[McAlister Field House]] for weightlifting, locker rooms, team meeting and video space, and academic tutoring.  The Citadel Sports Medicine Department also utilizes Seignious Hall.<ref>{{cite book|url=http://catalog.e-digitaleditions.com/title/10811|title=2011 Citadel Football Media Guide|publisher=e-digitaleditions.com|page=7|accessdate=2012-03-24}}</ref>\n\n==Coaches and staff==\nCoaches from The Citadel have often been targeted for larger programs. Former head and assistant coaches at The Citadel include [[Bobby Ross]], [[Charlie Taaffe]], [[Ellis Johnson (American football coach)|Ellis Johnson]], [[Frank Beamer]], [[Al Davis]], [[Ralph Friedgen]], and [[Mike Houston (American football)|Mike Houston]].<ref>{{cite book|url=http://catalog.e-digitaleditions.com/title/10811|pages=10\u201311|title=2011 Citadel Football Media Guide|publisher=e-digitaleditions.com|accessdate=2012-03-24}}</ref>\n\n===Head Coaches===\n{{Main|List of The Citadel Bulldogs head football coaches}}\n\n<ref>{{cite book|url=http://catalog.e-digitaleditions.com/title/10811|page=142|title=2011 Citadel Football Media Guide|publisher=e-digitaleditions.com|accessdate=2012-03-24}}</ref>\n{|class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n!Name\n!First Year\n!Final Year\n!No. Seasons\n|-\n|[[Syd Smith (baseball)|Syd Smith]]\n|1905\n|1905\n|1\n|-\n|[[Ralph Foster (American football coach)|Ralph Foster]]\n|1906\n|1908\n|3\n|-\n|[[Sam Costen]]\n|1909\n|1910\n|2\n|-\n|[[Louis LeTellier]]\n|1911\n|1912\n|2\n|-\n|[[George Rogers (American football coach)|George Rogers]]\n|1913\n|1919\n|4\n|-\n|[[Harvey O'Brien]]\n|1916\n|1921\n|5\n|-\n|[[Carl Prause]]\n|1922\n|1929\n|8\n|-\n|[[Johnny Floyd]]\n|1930\n|1931\n|2\n|-\n|[[Tatum Gressette]]\n|1932\n|1939\n|8\n|-\n|[[Bo Rowland]]\n|1940\n|1942\n|3\n|-\n|[[J. Quinn Decker]]\n|1946\n|1952\n|7\n|-\n|[[John D. McMillan]]\n|1953\n|1954\n|2\n|-\n|[[John Sauer]]\n|1955\n|1956\n|2\n|-\n|[[Eddie Teague]]\n|1957\n|1965\n|9\n|-\n|[[Red Parker]]\n|1966\n|1972\n|7\n|-\n|[[Bobby Ross]]\n|1973\n|1977\n|5\n|-\n|[[Art Baker (coach)|Art Baker]]\n|1978\n|1982\n|5\n|-\n|[[Tom Moore (American football coach, born 1945)|Tom Moore]]\n|1983\n|1986\n|4\n|-\n|[[Charlie Taaffe]]\n|1987\n|1995\n|9\n|-\n|[[Don Powers]]\n|1996\n|2000\n|5\n|-\n|[[Ellis Johnson (American football coach)|Ellis Johnson]]\n|2001\n|2003\n|3\n|-\n|[[John Zernhelt]]\n|2004\n|2004\n|1\n|-\n|[[Kevin Higgins (American football)|Kevin Higgins]]\n|2005\n|2013\n|9\n|-\n|[[Mike Houston (American football)|Mike Houston]]\n|2014\n|2015\n|2\n|-\n|[[Brent Thompson (American football)|Brent Thompson]]\n|2016\n|\n|3\n|}\n\n===Current Staff===\nThe current coaching staff at the Citadel is:<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.postandcourier.com/article/20140117/PC20/140119455/1032/drayton-returns-to-citadel|newspaper=Post and Courier|location=Charleston, SC|author=Jeff Hartsell|title=Citadel football welcomes back Maurice Drayton as 