ball|Tennessee Tech]] || '''W''' 27\u20130 \n|}\n\n===FCS Playoffs===\nThe Citadel has appeared in the [[NCAA Division I Football Championship|FCS Playoffs]] five times, posting a 2\u20135 record.\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align:center;\"\n|-\n{{CollegePrimaryHeader|team=The Citadel Bulldogs|Year|Round|Opponent|Result}}\n|-\n| [[1988 The Citadel Bulldogs football team|1988]]|| First Round|| [[Georgia Southern Eagles football|Georgia Southern]] || L 20\u201338\n|-\n| [[1990 The Citadel Bulldogs football team|1990]]|| First Round|| [[Georgia Southern Eagles football|Georgia Southern]] || L 0\u201331\n|-\n| [[1992 The Citadel Bulldogs football team|1992]]|| First Round<br>Quarterfinals || [[North Carolina A&T Aggies football|North Carolina A&T]]<br>[[Youngstown State Penguins football|Youngstown State]]|| '''W''' 44\u20130<br>L 17\u201342\n|-\n| [[2015 The Citadel Bulldogs football team|2015]]|| First Round<br>Second Round || [[Coastal Carolina Chanticleers football|Coastal Carolina]]<br>[[Charleston Southern Buccaneers football|Charleston Southern]] || '''W''' 41\u201338<br>L 6\u201314\n|-\n| [[2016 The Citadel Bulldogs football team|2016]]|| Second Round || [[Wofford Terriers football|Wofford]] || L 3\u201317\n|-\n|}\n\n==Rivalries==\n<!--rivalry records up to date through 2016 regular season-->{{see also|Military Classic of the South|The Citadel\u2013Furman football rivalry}}\nThe Citadel's primary rivals are the [[VMI Keydets football]] and [[Furman Paladins football]].  The game with VMI is known as the [[Military Classic of the South]].  The Citadel and Furman have been heated, annual rivals since both joined the Southern Conference in 1936.  The Citadel is 151-174-9 all-time against in-state opponents.\n\n{|class=\"wikitable\"\n!Opponent !!Wins !!Losses !!Ties !! First meeting !!Last Citadel win !!Last Opponent win\n|- align=\"center\"\n| [[VMI Keydets football|VMI]] || 42 || 31 || 2 || 1920 || 2018 || 2019\n|- align=\"center\"\n| [[Furman Paladins football|Furman]] || 37 || 60 || 3 || 1913 || 2019 || 2018\n|}\n\n'''Record vs. Current SoCon opponents'''<br>\n:''Excludes Furman and VMI, listed above.''\n:''East Tennessee State returned to the SoCon in 2016.''\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n!Opponent !!Wins !!Losses !!Ties !! First meeting !! Last Citadel win !! Last Opponent win\n|- align=\"center\"\n| [[Chattanooga Mocs football|Chattanooga]] || 19 || 30 || 2 || 1926 || 2017 || 2018\n|- align=\"center\"\n| [[East Tennessee State Buccaneers football|East Tennessee State]]{{efn|East Tennessee State did not sponsor football from 2004\u20132014}} || 11 || 16 || 0 || 1966 || 2017 || 2018\n|- align=\"center\"\n| [[Mercer Bears football|Mercer]]{{efn|Mercer did not sponsor football from 1941\u20132012}} || 10 || 5 || 1 || 1906 || 2018 || 2017\n|- align=\"center\"\n| [[Samford Bulldogs football|Samford]] || 7 || 5 || 0 || 1989 || 2018 || 2017\n|- align=\"center\"\n| [[Western Carolina Catamounts football|Western Carolina]] || 25 || 17 || 1 || 1972 || 2018 || 2017\n|- align=\"center\"\n| [[Wofford Terriers football|Wofford]] || 42 || 30 || 1 || 1916 || 2016 || 2018\n|}\n{{notelist}}\n\n'''Record vs instate opponents'''<br>\n:''Division 1, non-SoCon only''\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n!Opponent !!Wins !!Losses !!Ties !! First meeting !! Last Citadel win !! Last Opponent win\n|- align=\"center\"\n| [[Charleston Southern Buccaneers football|Charleston Southern]]{{efn|In 2018, Charleston Southern vacated three wins against The Citadel, including one from the 2015 playoffs, after NCAA sanctions.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.postandcourier.com/sports/charleston-southern-vacates-victories-big-south-titles-with-more-to/article_e7032d4c-fcaf-11e8-a431-63ab2d0803e0.html|newspaper=Post and Courier|author=David Shelton|date=December 10, 2018|accessdate=December 16, 2018|title=Charleston Southern vacates 122 victories, 3 Big South titles, with more to come}}</ref>}} || 6 || 2  || \u2014 || 2002 || 2018 || 2013\n|- align=\"center\"\n| [[Clemson Tigers football|Clemson]] || 5 || 32 || 1 || 1909 || 1931 || 2017\n|- align=\"center\"\n| [[Coastal Carolina Chanticleers football|Coastal Carolina]] || 1 || 1 || \u2014 || 2014 || 2015{{efn|The Bulldogs won a 2015 matchup in the first round of the [[2015 NCAA Division I FCS football season|FCS Playoffs]].}}  || 2014\n|- align=\"center\"\n| [[Presbyterian Blue Hose football|Presbyterian]] || 51 || 11 || 1 || 1915 || 2017 || 1979\n|- align=\"center\"\n| [[South Carolina Gamecocks football|South Carolina]] || 8 || 40 || 3 || 1905 || 2015 || 2011\n|- align=\"center\"\n| [[South Carolina State Bulldogs football|South Carolina State]] || 4 || 0 || 0 || 1989  || 2001 || none\n|}\n{{notelist}}\n\n==Bulldogs in professional football==\n{{main|List of The Citadel Bulldogs in the NFL Draft}}\nMany Citadel alumni have played in various professional leagues, including the [[National Football League]], [[Canadian Football League]] and [[Arena Football League]].  Sixteen players have been drafted in the [[NFL Draft]] and [[AFL Draft]], and other players have signed as undrafted free agents.  Likely the most famous Citadel alumni in professional football are Running Back [[Stump Mitchell]] and broadcaster [[Paul Maguire]].  Currently, [[Andre Roberts (American football)|Andre Roberts]] is a member of the [[Atlanta Falcons]] and [[Cortez Allen]] recently played with the [[Pittsburgh Steelers]] for 5 seasons; Running Back [[Travis Jervey]] played in 2 Super Bowls with the [[Green Bay Packers]] and was named an All Pro as a special teams player.<ref>{{cite book|url=http://catalog.e-digitaleditions.com/title/10811|title=2011 Citadel Football Media Guide|publisher=e-digitaleditions.com|page=12|accessdate=2012-03-24}}</ref>\n{{col-begin}}\n{{col-2}}\n'''[[National Football League Draft]]'''<br>\n{|class=\"wikitable\"\n!Year\n!Name\n!Round\n!Overall\n!Team\n|-\n|[[1939 NFL Draft|1939]]\n|[[Andy Sabados]]\n|13\n|111\n|[[History of the Arizona Cardinals#Chicago years (1898\u20131959)|Chicago Cardinals]]\n|-\n|[[1959 NFL Draft|1959]]\n|Pete Davidson\n|14\n|165\n|[[St. Louis Rams|Los Angeles Rams]]\n|-\n|rowspan=2|[[1960 NFL Draft|1960]]\n|Harry Rakowski\n|15\n|169\n|[[St. Louis Rams|Los Angeles Rams]]\n|-\n|Joe Davis\n|17\n|194\n|[[History of the Arizona Cardinals#Chicago years (1898\u20131959)|Chicago Cardinals]]\n|-\n|[[1969 NFL Draft|1969]]\n|Jim McMillan\n|16\n|415\n|[[Indianapolis Colts|Baltimore Colts]]\n|-\n|[[1970 NFL Draft|1970]]\n|[[John Small (American football)|John Small]]\n|1\n|12\n|[[Atlanta Falcons]]\n|-\n|[[1977 NFL Draft|1977]]\n|Brian Ruff\n|11\n|304\n|[[Indianapolis Colts|Baltimore Colts]]\n|-\n|[[1981 NFL Draft|1981]]\n|[[Stump Mitchell]]\n|9\n|226\n|[[Arizona Cardinals|St. Louis Cardinals]]\n|-\n|[[1987 NFL Draft|1987]]\n|[[Greg Davis (placekicker)|Greg Davis]]\n|9\n|246\n|[[Tampa Bay Buccaneers]]\n|-\n|[[1995 NFL Draft|1995]]\n|[[Travis Jervey]]\n|5\n|170\n|[[Green Bay Packers]]\n|-\n|[[2005 NFL Draft|2005]]\n|[[Nehemiah Broughton]]\n|7\n|222\n|[[Washington Redskins]]\n|-\n|[[2010 NFL Draft|2010]]\n|[[Andre Roberts (American football)|Andre Roberts]]\n|3\n|88\n|[[Arizona Cardinals]]\n|-\n|[[2011 NFL Draft|2011]]\n|[[Cortez Allen]]\n|4\n|128\n|[[Pittsburgh Steelers]]\n|}\n{{col-2}}\n'''[[American Football League Draft]]'''<br>\n{|class=\"wikitable\"\n!Year\n!Name\n!Round\n!Overall\n!Team\n|-\n|rowspan=5|[[1960 AFL Draft|1960]]\n|Wayne Stewart\n|\n|\n|rowspan=4|[[Los Angeles Chargers]]\n|-\n|Joe Davis\n|\n|\n|-\n|[[Paul Maguire]]\n|\n|\n|-\n|Pete Davidson\n|\n|\n|-\n|Harry Rakowski\n|\n|\n|[[Buffalo Bills]]\n|-\n|[[1964 AFL Draft|1964]]\n|Vince Petno\n|8\n|63\n|[[Oakland Raiders]]\n|}\n{{col-end}}\n\n==Individual honors==\n\n'''All-Americans'''<br>\n''This list includes selected First Team All-Americans at The Citadel<ref>{{cite book|url=http://catalog.e-digitaleditions.com/title/10811|title=2011 Citadel Football Media Guide|page=133|publisher=e-digitaleditions.com|accessdate=2012-08-14}}</ref>''\n{|class=wikitable\n! Year !! 