rican football)|Brent Thompson]]\n| HeadCoachYear    = 4th\n| HCWins           = 25 <!-- Through 2018 season -->\n| HCLosses         = 18 <!-- Through 2018 season -->\n| Stadium          = [[Johnson Hagood Stadium]]\n| FieldName        = Sansom Field\n| StadiumBuilt     = 1948\n| StadCapacity     = 21,000\n| StadSurface      = Natural Grass\n| Location         = [[Charleston, South Carolina]]\n| Conference = [[Southern Conference]]\n| ConfDivision     = \n| PastAffiliations = \n| ATWins           = 508\n| ATLosses         = 559\n| ATTies           = 32\n| BowlWins         = 1\n| BowlLosses       = 0\n| BowlTies         = \n| PlayoffApps      = 5\n| Playoffs         = 2\u20135\n| NatlTitles       = \n| ConfTitles       = 4 (1961, 1992, 2015, 2016)\n| DivTitles        = \n| Heismans         = \n| AllAmericans     = \n| uniform          =\n| FightSong        = \"The Fighting Light Brigade\"\n| MascotDisplay    = Bulldog\n| MarchingBand     = [[The Regimental Band and Pipes]]\n| WebsiteName      = citadelsports.com\n| WebsiteURL       = http://www.citadelsports.com\n}}\n'''The Citadel Bulldogs football''' program represents [[The Citadel, The Military College of South Carolina]] in the [[NCAA Division I FCS|NCAA Division I Football Championship Subdivision (FCS)]]. The Bulldogs play in the [[Southern Conference]], as they have since 1936.  The Bulldogs are coached by [[Brent Thompson (American football)|Brent Thompson]], who was hired on January 19, 2016 to replace [[Mike Houston (American football)|Mike Houston]], who became the head football coach of [[James Madison Dukes football|James Madison University]] on January 18, 2016.<ref>{{cite news|author=Jeff Hartsell|title=The Citadel introduces new football coach Mike Houston |url=http://www.postandcourier.com/article/20140109/PC20/140109440/1032/citadel-introduces-houston-as-new-coach|accessdate=January 9, 2014|newspaper=[[Post and Courier]] |location=Charleston, SC|date=January 9, 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.live5news.com/story/30994395/mike-houston-leaves-the-citadel-for-james-madison|title=Mike Houston leaves The Citadel for James Madison|author=Kevin Bilodeau|date=January 18, 2016|accessdate=January 18, 2016|publisher=[[WCSC-TV]]}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.live5news.com/story/31005256/report-the-citadel-to-name-brent-thompson-as-new-head-coach|publisher=WCSC-TV|title=The Citadel names Brent Thompson as new head coach |author=Kevin Bilodeau|date=January 19, 2016|accessdate=January 19, 2016}}</ref>\n\n==History==\n{{See also|List of The Citadel Bulldogs football seasons}}\n\n==Facilities==\nThe Bulldogs first recorded stadium was College Park, located in the northeast corner of [[Hampton Park (Charleston, SC)|Hampton Park]] in [[Charleston, South Carolina]]. This field predated the current [[College Park (Charleston)|College Park]] at the same site, which is used as a practice facility for [[The Citadel Bulldogs baseball]]. Due to increasing attendance and the poor state of the stadium, the Bulldogs moved to the original [[Johnson Hagood Stadium (1927)|Johnson Hagood Stadium]] in 1927. In 1948, that stadium was replaced by the current [[Johnson Hagood Stadium]], which lies just to the south of The Citadel's gates in Charleston. \n\n[[File:CitadelStadium.jpg|thumb|right|Johnson Hagood Stadium]]\nJohnson Hagood is a 21,000 seat stadium, in which The Citadel routinely ranks in the top 25 in attendance at the FCS level.  In 2001, the Altman Athletic Center opened in the south end zone, complete with new home and visitor's locker rooms, official's locker rooms, and an upstairs hospitality area for donors.  In 2008, The Citadel completed a re-construction of the west stands and West Side Tower.  The stands contain reserved premium seats and bleacher seats, while the tower, shared with the South Carolina National Guard, contains twelve suites, a club level, and state of the art press box.  During preparation for construction, workers discovered the remains of sailors from failed test runs of the ''[[H.L. Hunley (submarine)|H.L. Hunley]]''.  These remains were reinterred in Magnolia Cemetery in Charleston.\n\nBeginning in 2012, The Citadel implemented a points system for parking and seat selection in Johnson Hagood Stadium, joining many large programs who use similar systems. The program is designed to reward long-time and large donors to The Citadel athletics by giving them preference in selecting seat and parking locations.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://foundation.citadel.edu/Document.Doc?id=401|title=Priority Points System|publisher=The Citadel|accessdate=2012-05-12}}</ref>\n\nIn 2016, The Citadel determined that lead paint needed remediation on the east (visitor's) side of the stadium.  The work resulted in the entire east side being closed for the first game of the [[2016 The Citadel Bulldogs football team|2016 season]] and some sections being opened for subsequent games.  The capacity was thus 10,500 for the first game and about 15,000 for later games.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.postandcourier.com/20160829/160829380/citadel-considers-tearing-down-visitors-side-at-johnson-hagood-stadium|newspaper=Post and Courier|author=Jeff Hartsell|location=Charleston, SC|date=August 29, 2016|title=Citadel considers tearing down visitors\u2019 side at Johnson Hagood Stadium|accessdate=October 12, 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.postandcourier.com/20160909/160909467/citadel-football-returns-to-half-of-johnson-hagood-stadium|newspaper=Post and Courier|author=Jeff Hartsell|location=Charleston, SC|date=September 9, 2016|title=Citadel football returns to (half of) Johnson Hagood Stadium|accessdate=October 12, 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.postandcourier.com/20161011/161019898/citadel-home-at-last-with-nations-best-4-road-wins|newspaper=Post and Courier|author=Jeff Hartsell|location=Charleston, SC|date=October 11, 2016|title=Citadel home at last, with nation\u2019s best 4 road wins|accessdate=October 12, 2016}}</ref>  The Board of Visitors decided to fully renovate the east side of the stadium, announcing that decision on December 2, 2016.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.postandcourier.com/sports/citadel-notes-stadium-s-east-side-to-be-renovated-georgia/article_9ccf5690-b8ca-11e6-b48e-6b78a3d257d5.html|newspaper=Post and Courier|author=Jeff Hartsell|location=Charleston, SC|date=October 11, 2016|title=Citadel Notes: Stadium's east side to be renovated; Georgia Tech on 2019 schedule}}</ref>\n\n===Practice and on-campus facilities===\nPractices are held at the Maybank Triplets Practice Facility, an artificial turf field at the north edge of campus.  The Bulldogs utilize Seignious Hall, located across from [[McAlister Field House]] for weightlifting, locker rooms, team meeting and video space, and academic tutoring.  The Citadel Sports Medicine Department also utilizes Seignious Hall.<ref>{{cite book|url=http://catalog.e-digitaleditions.com/title/10811|title=2011 Citadel Football Media Guide|publisher=e-digitaleditions.com|page=7|accessdate=2012-03-24}}</ref>\n\n==Coaches and staff==\nCoaches from The Citadel have often been targeted for larger programs. Former head and assistant coaches at The Citadel include [[Bobby Ross]], [[Charlie Taaffe]], [[Ellis Johnson (American football coach)|Ellis Johnson]], [[Frank Beamer]], [[Al Davis]], [[Ralph Friedgen]], and [[Mike Houston (American football)|Mike Houston]].<ref>{{cite book|url=http://catalog.e-digitaleditions.com/title/10811|pages=10\u201311|title=2011 Citadel Football Media Guide|publisher=e-digitaleditions.com|accessdate=2012-03-24}}</ref>\n\n===Head Coaches===\n{{Main|List of The Citadel Bulldogs head football coaches}}\n\n<ref>{{cite book|url=http://catalog.e-digitaleditions.com/title/10811|page=142|title=2011 Citadel Football Media Guide|publisher=e-digitaleditions.com|accessdate=2012-03-24}}</ref>\n{|class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n!Name\n!First Year\n!Final Year\n!No. Seasons\n|-\n|[[Syd Smith (baseball)|Syd Smith]]\