dividually but lump them together.</small>\n\n==Results==\n===Early states===\n\n====Iowa====\nThe Iowa Democratic caucuses took place on February 3, 2020. The results of the 2020 Iowa caucuses have been certified; however, they have been challenged. As of February 29, 2020, that challenge is pending before the Democratic National Committee's Rules and Bylaws Committee.<ref name= \"certify\">{{cite news|url=https://www.cnn.com/2020/02/29/politics/iowa-democratic-caucuses-certified-results/index.html|title=Iowa Democratic Party certifies Buttigieg's Iowa lead amid Sanders challenge|work=CNN.com|last1=Levy|first1=Adam|last2=Merica|first2=Dan|date=March 1, 2020|access-date=March 1, 2020}}</ref>\n{{excerpt|2020 Iowa Democratic caucuses|fragment=IAresults}}\n\n====New Hampshire====\nThe New Hampshire Democratic primary took place on February 11, 2020.\n{{excerpt|2020 New Hampshire Democratic primary|fragment=NHresults}}\n\n====Nevada====\nThe Nevada Democratic caucus took place with early voting February 14 to 18, and was completed on February 22, 2020.\n{{excerpt|2020 Nevada Democratic caucuses|fragment=NVresults}}\n\n====South Carolina====\nThe South Carolina Democratic primary took place on February 29, 2020, three days prior to Super Tuesday.  \n{{excerpt|2020 South Carolina Democratic primary|fragment=SCresults}}\n\n===Super Tuesday===\n[[Super Tuesday]] took place on March 3, 2020.\n\n====Alabama====\n{{excerpt|2020 Alabama Democratic primary|fragment=ALresults}}\n\n====American Samoa====\n{{transcluded section|source=2020 United States presidential caucuses in American Samoa}}\n{{trim|{{#section-h:2020 United States presidential caucuses in American Samoa|Results}}}}\n\n====Arkansas====\n{{excerpt|2020 Arkansas Democratic primary|fragment=ARresults}}\n\n====California====\n{{transcluded section|source=2020 California Democratic primary}}\n{{trim|{{#section-h:2020 California Democratic primary|Results}}}}\n\n====Colorado====\n{{excerpt|2020 Colorado Democratic primary|fragment=COresults}}\n\n====Maine====\n{{excerpt|2020 Maine Democratic primary|fragment=MEresults}}\n\n====Massachusetts====\n{{excerpt|2020 Massachusetts Democratic primary|fragment=MAresults}}\n\n====Minnesota====\n{{excerpt|2020 Minnesota Democratic primary|fragment=MNresults}}\n\n====North Carolina====\n{{excerpt|2020 North Carolina Democratic primary|fragment=NCresults}}\n\n====Oklahoma====\n{{excerpt|2020 Oklahoma Democratic primary|fragment=OKresults}}\n\n====Tennessee====\n{{excerpt|2020 Tennessee Democratic primary|fragment=TNresults}}\n\n====Texas====\n{{excerpt|2020 Texas Democratic primary|fragment=TXresults}}\n\n====Utah====\n{{excerpt|2020 Utah Democratic primary|fragment=UTresults}}\n\n====Vermont====\n{{excerpt|2020 Vermont Democratic primary|fragment=VTresults}}\n\n====Virginia====\n{{excerpt|2020 Virginia Democratic primary|fragment=VAresults}}\n\n===Mid/Late-March===\n====Democrats Abroad====\n{{transcluded section|source=2020 Democrats Abroad primary}}\n{{trim|{{#section-h:2020 Democrats Abroad primary|Results}}}}\n\n====Idaho====\n{{transcluded section|source=2020 Idaho Democratic primary}}\n{{trim|{{#section-h:2020 Idaho Democratic primary|Results}}}}\n\n====Michigan====\n{{transcluded section|source=2020 Michigan Democratic primary}}\n{{trim|{{#section-h:2020 Michigan Democratic primary|Results}}}}\n\n====Mississippi====\n{{excerpt|2020 Mississippi Democratic primary|fragment=MSresults}}\n\n====Missouri====\n{{transcluded section|source=2020 Missouri Democratic primary}}\n{{trim|{{#section-h:2020 Missouri Democratic primary|Results}}}}\n\n====North Dakota====\n{{excerpt|2020 North Dakota Democratic caucuses|fragment=NDresults}}\n\n====Washington====\n{{excerpt|2020 Washington Democratic primary|fragment=WAresults}}\n\n====Northern Mariana Islands====\n{{transcluded section|source=2020 United States presidential caucuses in the Northern Mariana Islands}}\n{{trim|{{#section-h:2020 United States presidential caucuses in the Northern Mariana Islands|Results}}}}\n\n====Arizona====\n{{transcluded section|source=2020 Arizona Democratic primary}}\n{{trim|{{#section-h:2020 Arizona Democratic primary|Results}}}}\n\n====Florida====\n{{excerpt|2020 Florida Democratic primary|fragment=FLresults}}\n\n====Illinois====\n{{transcluded section|source=2020 Illinois Democratic primary}}\n{{trim|{{#section-h:2020 Illinois Democratic primary|Results}}}}\n\n===April===\n====Wisconsin====\n{{transcluded section|source=2020 Wisconsin Democratic primary}}\n{{trim|{{#section-h:2020 Wisconsin Democratic primary|Results}}}}\n\n====Alaska====\n{{excerpt|2020 Alaska Democratic primary|fragment=AKresults}}\n\n==Notes==\n{{notelist}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|refs=\n<ref name=\"GP\">{{cite web|title=Nevada Democratic Delegation 2020|url=https://www.thegreenpapers.com/P20/NV-D|publisher=The Green Papers|date=March 31, 2019|accessdate=April 12, 2019}}</ref> <!-- [[2020 Nevada Democratic caucuses#Procedure]] -->\n}}\n{{2020 Democratic primaries}}\n\n[[Category:2020 United States Democratic presidential primaries]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Selection of the Democratic Party nominee for president of the United States in 2020}}\n{{Use American English|date=January 2019}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=March 2020}}\n{{US 2020 presidential elections series}}\n\nThis article contains the '''results of the [[2020 Democratic Party presidential primaries]] and caucuses,''' the processes by which the [[Democratic Party (United States)|Democratic Party]] selects delegates to attend the [[2020 Democratic National Convention]] from July 13\u201316, 2020. The series of [[primaries]], [[caucuses]], and state conventions will culminate in the national convention, where the delegates cast their votes to formally select a candidate. A simple majority (1,990) of the total delegate votes (3,979) is required to become the nominee. No candidate has yet reached this threshold.\n\nThe campaign for the 2020 Democratic presidential nomination began on July 28, 2017, when [[Maryland's 6th congressional district|Maryland Congressman]] [[John Delaney (Maryland politician)|John Delaney]] became the first candidate to announce his run for [[President of the United States|president]]. By April 2019, more than 20 major candidates were recognized by national and state polls, causing the field of 2020 major Democratic presidential candidates to exceed the field of major candidates in the [[2016 Republican Party presidential primaries]] as the largest presidential candidate field for any single U.S. political party in a single election cycle.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.washingtonexaminer.com/news/campaigns/biden-entry-makes-2020-democrats-the-largest-presidential-field-in-history|title=Biden entry makes 20 Democrats in 2020: The largest presidential field in history|date=April 24, 2019|website=Washington Examiner}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://time.com/5607309/democratic-primaries-with-most-candidates/|title=What the 2020 Democrats Can Learn From One of the Most Crowded Primary Fields in History|website=Time}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.politifact.com/article/2019/may/02/big-democratic-primary-field-what-need/|title=PolitiFact - The record-setting 2020 Democratic primary field: What you need to know|website=@politifact}}</ref> With the addition of [[Michael Bloomberg]] on November 24, 2019, the number of major Democratic presidential candidates in the 2020 Democratic primaries totaled 29.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.bloomberg.com/graphics/democratic-party-candidates-running-2020-election/|title=How the Massive Democratic Field Shrank to a Handful of Front-Runners|work=[[Bloomberg News]]|author1=Lauren Leatherby|author2=Paul Murray|date=March 2, 2020|accessdate=March 3, 2020}}</ref>  \n\nWhen voting began in the [[2020 Iowa Democratic caucuses|2020 Iowa caucuses]], 11 major candidates were actively campaigning. Democratic primaries and caucuses in early states yielded a controversial and disputed victory for [[Pete Buttigieg]] in the Iowa caucuses, a narrow victory for [[Bernie Sanders]] in the [[2020 New Hampshire Democratic primary|New Hampshire primary]] over Buttigieg, a victory for Sanders in the [[2020 Nevada Democratic caucuses|Nevada caucuses]], and a victory for [[Joe Biden]] in the [[2020 South Carolina Democratic primary|South Carolina primary]]. Sanders won the popular vote in both Iowa and New Hampshire, with New Hampshire generally considered a win for Sanders.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.businessinsider.com/bernie-won-iowa-popular-vote-buttigieg-electoral-college-2020-2?amp&r=US&IR=T|title=Why Bernie Sanders won Iowa's popular vote, but Pete Buttigieg may win the state's Electoral College|work=[[Business Insider]]|date=February 6, 2020|accessdate=March 9, 2020|author=John Haltiwanger and Walt Hickey}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2020/02/11/us/politics/bernie-sanders-new-hampshire-primary.html|title= Bernie Sanders Scores Narrow Victory in New Hampshire Primary|work=[[NYTimes]]|author=Jonathan Martin and Alexander Burns|date=February 12, 2020|accessdate=March 9, 2020}}</ref> Before the March 3, 2020, Super Tuesday primaries, six major candidates ended their campaigns; Bloomberg and [[Elizabeth Warren]] ended their campaigns due to poor showings on Super Tuesday.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.cbsnews.com/news/bloomberg-ends-presidential-bid-biden-endorsement-super-tuesday/|title=Bloomberg ends presidential run and endorses Biden after Super Tuesday rejection|work=[[CBS News]]|date=March 4, 2020|accessdate=March 5, 2020|author=Tim Perry}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://abc7ny.com/politics/elizabeth-warren-drops-out-of-race-for-president/5987361/|title=Elizabeth Warren drops out of 2020 race for president|work=[[WABC-TV]]|author=|date=March 5, 2020|accessdate=March 5, 2020}}</ref> [[Tulsi Gabbard]] ended her campaign on March 19.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.usatoday.com/story/news/politics/elections/2020/03/19/tulsi-gabbard-ends-presidential-campaign/2009989001/|title=Tulsi Gabbard ends presidential campaign, backs Joe Biden|work=[[USA Today]]|author1=Jason Lalljee|author2=Rebecca Morin|date=March 19, 2020|accessdate=March 19, 2020}}</ref> Sanders ended his campaign on April 8.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2020/04/08/us/politics/bernie-sanders-drops-out.html|title=Bernie Sanders Drops Out of 2020 Democratic Race for President?|date=April 8, 2020|website=[[New York Times]]|access-date=April 8, 2020}}</ref> Joe Biden is the only major Democratic candidate remaining in the race.\n\n{{TOC limit|3}}\n\n==Overview of results==\n{| style=\"float; margin-left: 1em; margin-bottom: 0.5em\" class=\"infobox\"\n|+Map legend\n|-\n| style=\"padding: 0 5px;\" | {{colorbox|#224192}} Joe Biden\n|-\n| style=\"padding: 0 5px;\" | {{colorbox|#ba55d3}} Michael Bloomberg\n|-\n| style=\"padding: 0 5px;\" | {{colorbox|#f2ba42}} Pete Buttigieg\n|-\n| style=\"padding: 0 5px;\" | {{colorbox|#43b3ae}} Amy Klobuchar\n|-\n| style=\"padding: 0 5px;\" | {{colorbox|#228b22}} Bernie Sanders\n|-\n| style=\"padding: 0 5px;\" | {{colorbox|#d2691e}} Tom Steyer\n|-\n| style=\"padding: 0 5px;\" | {{colorbox|#b61b28}} Elizabeth Warren\n|-\n| style=\"padding: 0 5px;\" | {{colorbox|#666666}} Tie\n|-\n| style=\"padding: 0 5px;\" | {{colorbox|#999999}} ''Winner not yet declared''\n|}\n<center><gallery widths=\"500\" heights=\"310\">\nFile:Democratic Party presidential primaries results, 2020.svg|<small><center>A map of 2020 Democratic Party presidential primary and caucus results. It reflects the winners, measured by the number of pledged delegates, in each state. The delegate count set forth in this map is subject to change because (a) an appeal of the results of the Iowa caucuses is pending; and (b) the South Carolina delegate totals are estimated.</center></small>\n<br><br>\nFile:Democratic Party presidential primaries results by county, 2020.svg|<small><center>A map of 2020 Democratic Party presidential primary and caucus results by county. </center></small>\n</gallery></center>\n\n==Major candidates==\nThe table below shows candidates who have dropped out of the race during the primaries, and those who are still running, who have placed third or better in a state contest or earned at least one national delegate.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Burns|first1=Alexander|last2=Flegenheimer|first2=Matt|last3=Lee|first3=Jasmine C.|last4=Lerer|first4=Lisa|last5=Martin|first5=Jonathan|title=Who's Running for President in 2020?|url=https://www.nytimes.com/interactive/2019/us/politics/2020-presidential-candidates.html|newspaper=[[The New York Times]]|date=January 21, 2019|accessdate=March 10, 2019|url-access=limited|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190219132542/https://www.nytimes.com/interactive/2019/us/politics/2020-presidential-candidates.html|archive-date=February 19, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last1=Scherer|first1=Michael|last2=Uhrmacher|first2=Kevin|last3=Schaul|first3=Kevin|title=Who is hoping to challenge Trump for president in 2020?|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/graphics/2018/politics/2020-presidential-hopefuls/|newspaper=The Washington Post|date=May 14, 2018|accessdate=March 10, 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181014085144/https://www.washingtonpost.com/graphics/2018/politics/2020-presidential-hopefuls/|archive-date=October 14, 2018|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last1=Krishnakumar|first1=Priya|last2=Hook|first2=Janet|title=Who's running for president and who's not|url=https://www.latimes.com/projects/la-na-pol-2020-presidential-candidates/|newspaper=[[Los Angeles Times]]|date=January 13, 2019|accessdate=March 10, 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190307204159/https://www.latimes.com/projects/la-na-pol-2020-presidential-candidates/|archive-date=March 7, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last1=Klahr|first1=Renee|last2=Sadiq|first2=Alena|last3=Montanaro|first3=Domenico|last4=Hurt|first4=Alyson|title=Which Democrats Are Running In 2020\u2014And Which Still Might|url=https://www.npr.org/2019/01/31/689980506/which-democrats-are-running-in-2020-and-which-still-might|website=[[NPR]]|date=January 31, 2019|accessdate=March 10, 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190310042043/https://www.npr.org/2019/01/31/689980506/which-democrats-are-running-in-2020-and-which-still-might|archive-date=March 10, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last1=de Vries|first1=Karl|last2=Kelly|first2=Caroline|title=Here are the Democrats who have said they're running for president|url=https://www.cnn.com/2019/01/21/politics/2020-democrats-running-for-president/index.html|website=[[CNN]]|date=January 21, 2019|accessdate=March 10, 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190306220146/https://www.cnn.com/2019/01/21/politics/2020-democrats-running-for-president/index.html|archive-date=March 6, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=2020 presidential election: Track which candidates are running|url=https://www.axios.com/2020-presidential-election-candidates-announce-running-15472039-9bf49de4-351a-46b3-bdde-b980947b21ea.html|publisher=Axios|date=January 11, 2019|accessdate=March 10, 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190308081036/https://www.axios.com/2020-presidential-election-candidates-announce-running-15472039-9bf49de4-351a-46b3-bdde-b980947b21ea.html|archive-date=March 8, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n{| style=\"text-align:center; margin:15px 0; line-height:13px;\" cellpadding=\"0\"\n|-\n! Legend:&nbsp;&nbsp;\n|\n!  style=\"padding:11px 8px; background:#66b2ff;\"| <small>1st place<br/>pledged delegates</small>\n|\n!  style=\"padding:11px 8px; background:#99ccff;\"| <small>2nd place</small>\n|\n!  style=\"padding:11px 8px; background:#cce5ff;\"| <small>3rd place</small>\n|\n!  style=\"padding:11px 8px; background:#ccc;\"| <small>Candidate has<br />withdrawn</small>\n|\n!  style=\"padding:11px 8px; background:#aaa;\"| <small>Candidate unable to<br/> appea